<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows Continued Support for Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said today that Turkey will continue its support for the
just cause of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference here with visiting
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat following their talks,
Demirel emphasized that neither side of the Middle East peace
talks should not lose this golden opportunity because the process
was very important for peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey had attached great importance to the
implementation of the agreements between the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and Israel, adding that both sides should avoid
acts which might produce negative impact on the peace march.
</P>
<P>
On Israel's announcement to build new settlements in east
Jerusalem, Demirel said Turkey had criticized this move,
describing it as contradicting the principle of the PNA-Israeli
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president was critical of Israel's blocking of
Palestinian workers from going to their jobs in Israel.
</P>
<P>
"While the world is coming to Palestine's aid economically,
the economic blockade by Israel is making the Palestinians lose
billions of dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Turkish-Palestinian relations, Demirel said there
were no serious political problems between the two sides, adding
that Turkey was determined to further its relations with
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
In response, Arafat said the Turkish-Palestinian relations
were based on strategic, historical, contemporary and cultural
principles. He expressed his appreciation for Turkey's support in
their difficult days.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also voiced his gratitude to Turkey for its
participation in the international force monitoring the handover
of the West Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The international force monitoring the handover of Hebron
includes troops from Denmark, Italy, Sweden, Switzerland, Norway
and Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
