<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Housing Starts Up by 2 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. housing starts rose by
2 percent in January helped by a surge in single-family activity,
U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the construction of new homes and
apartments totaled 1.35 million at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate, up from the revised 1.32 million in December.
</P>
<P>
Single-family starts, about 80 percent of the total starting,
shot up by 10.2 percent to a 1.11 million rate, erasing a 11.3
percent loss in December.
</P>
<P>
But construction of apartments and condominiums, often volatile
but not as sensitive to interest-rate changes, plunged by 23.9
percent to a 242,000 rate after dropping 9.9 percent the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, housing starts surged by 22.2 percent in the
Northeast and shot up by 29.8 percent in the West. But they fell
by 13.2 percent in the Midwest and off 6.8 percent in the South.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that applications for building permits --
often a barometer of future activity -- slipped by 1.9 percent in
January to a 1.40 million rate from 1.42 million a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
After setting an eight-year high in 1996, most analysts have
expected that U.S. housing construction would slow down this year
while still continuing at a strong level.
</P>
<P>
The department had reported previously that 1.47 million homes
and apartments were built last year, up from 1.35 million in 1995
and the highest level since 1.49 million in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
