<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Remain in Contact with US on Helms-Burton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Sir. Leon Brittan, European
Commissioner for Foreign Trade, said the European Union(EU) would
remain in close bilateral contact with the US regarding the
controversial Helms-Burton Act following the nomination of the
panelists by the WTO Director-General on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides had made good progress but their
negotiation had not yet produced an outcome the EU considered
sufficient to suspend its action before the World Trade
Organization(WTO).
</P>
<P>
"This nomination is a purely procedural step which does not
signify a change of a gear in the EU's complaint against the
Helms-Burton Act," Sir. Leon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the Panel was becoming operational "in no
way limits our ability to continue bilateral negotiations", adding
that "further clarification, examination and discussion are
needed".
</P>
<P>
"Of course the Panel procedure can be halted or suspended at
any time if the parties reach agreement," the Commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
The Helm-Burton Act allows naturalized US citizens to sue
foreign firms or individuals doing business with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Because of strong opposition from US's major trade partners
including EU, Canada and Mexico, US President Clinton has twice
suspended that provision for six months - the last time on January
3.
</P>
<P>
The EU has condemned this Act as "extraterritorial" and
decided in last October to take the matter to the WTO dispute
settlement panel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
