<HEADLINE> Non-Communist Personages Mourn Deng's Death (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of China's
non-Communist parties and the All-China Federation of Industry and
Commerce, and personages without party affiliations today mourned
the death of Deng Xiaoping, who passed away Wednesday night in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They recalled the outstanding achievements and contributions of
the 93-year-old Deng, paying the utmost respect and expressing
their heartfelt grief over his death.
</P>
<P>
Lei Jieqiong, vice-chairwoman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's legislature, and
chairwoman of the Central Committee of the China Association for
Promoting Democracy, said that Deng is recognized by the Chinese
people of all ethnic groups, including the non-Communist parties,
as an outstanding leader with high prestige.
</P>
<P>
Under the guidance of Deng's theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics and the Party's basic line, she noted,
China's economic construction has achieved unprecedented success,
and profound changes have taken place in the country.
</P>
<P>
"If it were not for Comrade Deng Xiaoping, China would not have
had the reforms, opening up, and socialist modernization
construction, just as there would not have been a socialist New
China without the late Chairman Mao Zedong," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Her views were shared by Cheng Siyuan, vice chairman of the NPC
Standing Committee and a non-party personage, and Yang Jike,
executive vice chairman of the Central Committee of the China Zhi
Gong Party, who pointed out that the great merits of Deng in the
fields of economy, politics, diplomacy, education, science and
technology, culture, and military affairs have not only been
remembered in the hearts of Chinese people of various ethnic
groups, but also earned him a high reputation among the overseas
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"He devoted his entire life to the motherland and the people,
and people of the motherland love and adore him," they added.
</P>
<P>
Ding Shisun, chairman of the Central Committee of the China
Democratic League, said that Deng's theory of building socialism
with Chinese characteristics is deeply rooted in Chinese people's
hearts and across China's vast territory.
</P>
<P>
He recalled the National Day parade in Beijing in 1984, when
young students from Beijing University unfolded a banner on which
was written the words "Hello, Xiaoping."
</P>
<P>
"I was then president of the university, and therefore knew it
was a sheer voluntary act by the students," he noted. "It
reflected the sincere love and esteem for Comrade Deng Xiaoping
among people from various ethnic groups of China, as well as their
hearty support for the Party's lines, principles, and policies
since the third plenum of the 11th CPC Central Committee."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
