<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Urged to Protect Sugar Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 20 (Xinhua) -- An industrial official has
appealed to the Kenyan government to protect local sugar
companies from unscrupulous importers.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held on Wednesday in Kisumu, western
Kenya, Norman Brooks, National Vice-Chairman of the Federation of
Kenya Employers, said that local sugar companies are now having
70,000 tons of sugar in store.
</P>
<P>
The amount of sugar is unable to sell due to the flooding of
Kenyan market with cheap imported sugar, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that imported sugar from Brazil, Thailand,
Mauritius, South Africa and Swaziland meant for neighboring
countries is being diverted to the local market at low prices
because no duty has been paid.
</P>
<P>
Unless the government intervened to save the local companies,
Brooks said, more than 30,000 employees in the sugar industry
which is the main economic activities in western Kenya would lose
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Some of the sugar factories have now been forced to reduce
their prices so as to remain in business, said the official,
adding that only the best managed companies could survive even if
their sugar is sold at the current price.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that local sugar could compete with imported
sugar only if the government ensures that all imports are
authorized by the Kenya Sugar Authority and all duties and levies
are paid.
</P>
<P>
If the industry dies, the official stressed, about two million
people would lose their source of income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
