<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Natural Gas Imports Up 16 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany's natural gas imports
last year rose by 16.3 percent to 2.96 million terajoules from
1995, worth 10.8 billion marks (6.4 billion U.S. dollars), the
Federal Office of the Economy reported today.
</P>
<P>
The office said the natural gas import bill soared by almost 23
percent from 8.7 billion marks in 1995, also as a result of a 6
percent increase in prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Germany's oil imports rose by 2.2 percent to 102.9
million tons last year, costing 23.9 billion marks, or a 28.5
percent increase over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Germany imports natural gas mainly from Russia, the
Netherlands, Norway, Denmark and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Terajoule is a unit of measurement based on the energy
equivalent of the gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
