<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Secret Agents Warned in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Director General of the
National Intelligence Agency of South Africa Sizakele Sigxashe
today said his agency is watching closely foreign secret agents
flooding into the country.
</P>
<P>
The intelligence chief told a press conference in Cape Town
that some of the agents appear bent on subverting the government
of President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the number of foreign spies operating in
South Africa has doubled or trebled since the country's first
non-racial general elections in April 1994.
</P>
<P>
Sigxashe said all foreign embassies in the country have
declared their officials to security agencies here. But other
missions are yet to do so.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that many foreign spy agencies have moved their
African monitoring posts elsewhere in the continent to this
country since the 1994 polls.
</P>
<P>
These secret agents are interested in economic and
technological intelligence and some have taken particular
interest in arms programs here, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
