<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Communist Personages Mourn Deng's Death (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central leaders of the non-communist parties had close
contacts with Deng Xiaoping, and enjoyed true friendship with him.
</P>
<P>
With deep feeling, and based on their personal experiences,
they recalled Deng's careful concern for various non-communist
parties and non-party figures over the past dozens of years,
viewing him as an important member of the first generation of the
leadership of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) and the core of
the second generation of the leadership of the CPC.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jieping, Vice Chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC) and Chairman of the Central
Committee of the Jiu San (September 3) Society, as well as Qian
Weichang, Vice Chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference and Honorary Chairman of the Central
Committee of the China Democratic League, reviewed Deng's
tremendous contributions to the development of China's scientific,
technological and educational undertakings.
</P>
<P>
Lu Jiaxi, Vice Chairman of the NPC Standing Committee and
Chairman of the Central Committee of the Chinese Peasants and
Workers Democratic Party, added that Deng believed scientific work
was of greatest importance.
</P>
<P>
When meeting with scientists who had developed China's
electron-positron collider, Deng told them that in the process of
socialist modernization, the question of scientific development
should be thoroughly considered, and those scientific projects
that are prominent on the international scene should be developed
vigorously, according to Lu.
</P>
<P>
History has proved that Deng's idea was a strategic decision
that showed great foresight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
