<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Protecting Consumer Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Organization
of Consumer Unions (IOCU) today said Zimbabwe is among the few
African countries that have made great strides in protecting
consumer rights.
</P>
<P>
IOCU program coordinator for eastern and southern Africa
Ngaite Chimbandi said here a study carried out in 1995 showed
Zimbabwe and South Africa were the only African countries that
had embraced United Nations guidelines on consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
She said out of the 56 countries involved in the study, the
two southern African countries were the only ones with active
consumer rights watchdogs through the Consumer Council of
Zimbabwe (CCZ) and South African Consumer Coordination Council.
</P>
<P>
She noted, however, that there is need to come up with
comprehensive consumer legislations to ensure easy implementation
of consumer laws, adding that at present most statutes are
administered by different government ministries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
