<HEADLINE> Siemens Wants to Be Among World Top-10 Semiconductor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Siemens AG today said
that it wants to become one of the world's top-ten semiconductor
producers by tripling its chip turnover to about 15 billion marks
(8.9 billion U.S. dollars) by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Siemens aims to expanding its production in the more lucrative
logic chips for guidance and control functions in the automobile
and telecommunication industries, the German news agency DPA
quoted Siemens board member Ulrich Schumacher as saying.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher also said that chip prices, which had dropped
consistently on the world market, had now touched bottom and were
expected to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
Siemens, Germany's largest electronics and engineering company,
had managed to advance from the 19th to 12th place among the
world's chip makers during the past three years, Schumacher said.
Its chip turnover in the financial year ended September 30, 1996
were 4.6 billion marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
