<HEADLINE> Zairean Warring Sides Start Talks in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government has begun sponsoring a series of talks between
representatives of the warring sides in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for President Nelson Mandela, who is hosting the
meeting, said today the talks are taking place in South Africa's
legislative capital, Cape town.
</P>
<P>
The the spokesman said details of the discussions will not be
made public.
</P>
<P>
A representative of rebel leader Laurent Kabila and President
Mobutu Sese Seko's nephew and chief security adviser, Ngbada
Ayumba, are examining peace proposals to end the civil war,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations were tabled and endorsed by the United
Nations Security council and President Yoweri Museveni of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The initiative includes an immediate cease-fireee, withdrawal of
all foreign troops, including mercenaries, and respect for the
territorial integrity of Zaire and other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Under-secretary for Africa George Moose is monitoring the
talks in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela said yesterday he would today host talks
between the warring sides of Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
