<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Recommends Three Virus Strains Against Influenza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has recommended three virus strains that should be used to
produce vaccines for the 1997-1998 influenza season.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of international experts held on Wednesday at the
WHO headquarters in Geneva, the group of influenza experts advised
national health authorities and pharmaceutical companies on the
three selected virus strains, a type A (H3N2) strain, a type A
(H1N1) and a type B strain.
</P>
<P>
As in previous years, the specific viruses used in vaccine
manufacturing in each country will need to be approved by the
national control authorities.
</P>
<P>
"Influenza causes epidemics worldwide every year. WHO strongly
recommends the use of vaccine as a sound preventive measure
against this potentially fatal disease," WHO says, adding:
"Special attention should be paid to vaccinate the elderly,
individuals with immunodeficiency, sufferers of chronic diseases
of the heart or lungs as well as diabetes and other metabolic
disorders."
</P>
<P>
The detection of new influenza viruses is made possible through
the WHO network for influenza surveillance and control. This
network helps WHO monitor influenza activity in all regions of the
world and ensures that WHO receives influenza virus isolates and
information needed to select the new variants which will be used
to produce influenza vaccines for the next influenza season.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO, the epidemics in many countries reached a
peak around the end of December 1996 or during January 1997. In
central and eastern Europe, influenza activity increased around
mid-January.
</P>
<P>
Influenza A viruses were isolated worldwide and were almost
exclusively of the influenza A (H3N2) subtype. However, most
influenza virus isolates from Asia were influenza B with the
exception of Japan, where influenza A (H3N2) predominated. In
North America and parts of Europe, influenza B was frequently
reported, either along with influenza A or following the decline
of influenza A activity. Only a few laboratory confirmed cases of
influenza A (H1N1) have been reported so far this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
