<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Hospital Waiting Lists Grow to 1.1 million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of patients waiting
for hospital treatment in England is rising, with waiting lists up
by over three percent to a record high of 1.1 million at the end
of December, official figures showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health (DH) said that the total number of
people waiting, the number waiting for less than a year, the
number waiting for more than a year and the number waiting over 18
months have all increased in England.
</P>
<P>
There was a 3.2 percent rise in the overall numbers in the
three months from September to December 1996, giving a total of
1,096,000.
</P>
<P>
The rise included a sharp jump in patients waiting for more
than a year, an increase of 6,900, or 46 percent, to 21,900.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of patients waiting for more than 18
months, breaching the government's guarantee under the Patient's
Charter, rose from 25 to 123.
</P>
<P>
The DH said that a four percent increase in emergency
admissions this winter forced hospitals to cancel and delay
non-urgent treatments.
</P>
<P>
Philip Hunt, director of the National Association of Health
Authorities and Trusts, said that financial difficulty was another
factor leading to the rise of the waiting lists, with the National
Health Service struggling this year to cope with its toughest
financial settlement for a decade.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that official figures for the current quarter
may well show a further deterioration.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that while the increases were relatively small,
they were a setback for the government in the run-up to the
general election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
