<HEADLINE> Hong Kong People Mourn Deng's Death (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten, Chief Secretary Anson Chan,
Financial Secretary Donald Tang, the U.S., Japanese and Australian
consuls-general in Hong Kong, and British senior representative on
the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group (JLG) Hugh Davies were among
the mourners.
</P>
<P>
"His concept of 'one country, two systems' helped to make
possible the successful negotiation of the Joint Declaration, and
thus to lay the foundation for Hong Kong's stability and
prosperity after 1997," said Christopher Pattern in a statement
early this morning.
</P>
<P>
He said that Deng Xiaoping will be regarded by future
generations as a historic figure.
</P>
<P>
The mourning hall will open to the public from 9:30 a.m. to
5:00 p.m. from February 21 to 24. The five-star flag flew at half
mast over the building of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch
today.
</P>
<P>
All Hong Kong Newspapers today devoted full pages to tracing
the 93-year life path of the Chinese leader, his contributions to
China's economic and political reforms and his strategic
farsightedness in the reunification of China.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po's commentary says that the best way to mark the
great man is to continue the reform and opening up to the outside
world and bring China into a more prosperous new century under
the third-generation leadership with President Jiang Zemin at the
core.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Immortal is Deng Xiaoping, the son of the Chinese
people," Ta Kung Po's commentary praises Deng as the general
architect of China's reform and opening policy and modernization
process, and the founder of the theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics. The article says that Hong Kong people
are grateful to Deng because his scientific concept of "one
country, two systems" has laid down a solid basis for the
long-term stability and prosperity of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong today, the death of Deng Xiaoping has caused
strong reactions. Many people stayed before TV sets for hours to
watch the news and reports, and the sales of newspapers is
obviously increased than usual.  
</P>
