<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Leaves Key Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany's central bank left its
key interest rates unchanged today, and experts believe latest
fundamental price and monetary data has made any rate cut unlikely
at present.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank's discount rate remains at 2.5 percent and the
Lombard at 4.5 percent. The last cut in these two rates occurred
in mid-April 1996, each by half a point.
</P>
<P>
The Lombard rate is the ceiling at which the central bank lends
to commercial banks, and the discount rate generally is the lower
rate it makes available to meet bank liquidity needs.
</P>
<P>
The third key rate, the security repurchase offer, was kept at
3.0 percent, where it has been since last August.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank Chief Wednesday said he did not rule out the
possibility to introduce further cuts in the key rates. However,
experts believe that the latest fundamental price and monetary
data has made such change unlikely at this time.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank earlier today reported that the broad-based M3
money supply soared by 11.7 percent in January over the level of
the fourth quarter of 1996. The target corridor it has set for the
M3 supply expansion is at 3.5 to 6.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The wholesale prices in January disclosed today registered the
highest monthly jump in 18 months, with an increase of 1.2 percent
over December.
</P>
<P>
In addition, official data released last week showed that
overall inflation last month grew by 1.5 percent from December,
boosting the annual price rise rate to 1.8 percent, compared with
1.4 percent in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Remains Optimistic Over Economic Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany remains optimistic over
its economic forecast for 1997 and will be able to meet the strict
criteria necessary for joining the single European currency, said
German Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt today.
</P>
<P>
"I stand by the key data of the annual economic report: 2.5
percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth in 1997, after 1.4
percent last year," Rexrodt told the German parliament despite
pessimistic reports on the country's economic outlook,
</P>
<P>
Rexrodt stressed that Germany will meet the debt and budget
deficit criteria set for the planned 1999 single currency.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht Treaty for the European Union's single
currency program, the budget deficit and national debt of a member
country must not exceed 3 and 60 percent respectively of its GDP.
</P>
<P>
"The single currency must and will be as stable as the German
mark," the German news agency DPA quoted Rexrodt as saying.
</P>
<P>
Germany's central bank, known as Deutsche Bandesbank, Wednesday
said that in the fourth quarter of 1996, Germany's GDP showed
virtually zero growth, and possibly a decline, compared with the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Institute for the German Economy (DIW), one of the six
leading independent economic research institutes in the country,
also said Wednesday that it was revising its January projection of
a slight increase for the economy and now expects a 0.25 percent
decline in the first quarter of 1997 compared with the last
quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Germany's unemployment soared to a past-war record of nearly
4.66 million in January. Other disappointing data include
declining consumption, a recession in the building sector and
sluggish investments.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the only bright spot in the whole picture
was foreign demand which had kept export strong, a trend supported
by the softer German mark.
</P>
<P>
The DIW said that the performance of German export will be a
key factor to decide whether the economy will drop into recession
or not in the second quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
