<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gambling Turnover in Greece Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Greeks gambled a massive 646.1
billion drachmas or approximately 2.6 billion U.S. dollars in
1996, compared to 494.5 billion drachmas (about 2 billion dollars)
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released today by the National Statistics
Service (NSS), casinos earned the lion's share with a turnover of
241.6 billion drachmas (970 million dollars), marking a massive
273.1 percent increase over the 1995 figure of 64.7 billion
drachmas (260 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the 241.6 billion drachmas, privately-owned casinos, many of
which opened only recently, raked in 230.3 billion drachmas (920
million dollars), against 51.9 billion drachmas (208 million
dollars) in 1995. State controlled casinos earned 11.3 billion
drachmas (45.2 million dollars), compared to 12.8 billion drachmas
(51.2 billion dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the NSS, lottery tickets and instant lottery
scratch cards accounted for 178 billion drachmas (712 million
dollars) of the total in 1996, down on the 1995 figure of 190.3
billion drachmas (760 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Punters gambled 168 billion drachmas (672 million dollars) on
the football pools, compared to 186.5 billion drachmas (746
million dollars) in 1995, while horseracing bets accounted for
56.4 billion drachmas (226 million dollars) against 52 billion
drachmas (208 million dollars) in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
