<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Leaders Mourns Deng's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders across the
Asia-Pacific region today paid tribute to late Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping, hailing him as a great statesman who brought prosperity
and stability to the 1.2 billion Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Singaporean President Ong Teng Cheong, Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong and Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew each sent a condolence
letter on Deng's death, describing him as a "giant among world
leaders."
</P>
<P>
Goh said Deng brought about the greatest economic revolution in
history that had also affected the lives of others in Asia.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Young-sam sent a telegram to Chinese
President Jiang Zemin, hailing Deng as "an outstanding political
leader who opened a new chapter in world history."
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's Second Prime Minister Hun Sen said in his condolence
message that Deng's death is "one of the great losses in Chinese
and world history" since Deng has improved the lives of more than
one billion Chinese and also contributed to regional and world
peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Deng, who died late on Wednesday, introduced economic reforms
in 1978. His reform policies have since helped open China to the
outside world and deliver year-on-year economic growth of more
than nine percent.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto praised Deng for not
only pushing China's modernization forward but also making great
accomplishments in the development of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh in a message to his
Chinese counterpart Li Peng described Deng as an old friend of the
Thai people, adding that his role in promoting friendship and
peace will always be remembered.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard sent a telegram to Li
Peng and said the growing prosperity of China is Deng's "enduring
legacy".
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Vietnam in their respective condolences also hailed
Deng as a great statesman and expressed deep sorrows over his
death. 
</P>
