<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Crime Falls Last Yera: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of most frequently
committed crimes in the Netherlands declined across the board last
year, the Dutch daily newspaper Het Financieele Dagblad reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting figures from the national statistics office CBS, the
newspaper reported that the police registered four million
incidents of theft, assault, vandalism and hit-and-run accidents
in 1996, half a million less than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
CBS said this was the largest decline in crime figures since it
began collecting statistics in 1980.
</P>
<P>
There were some 1.67 million reports of theft in 1996 by
victims aged over 15, or 300,000 fewer than in 1995. Incidents of
assault declined by 120,000 to 722,000.
</P>
<P>
Reports of vandalism declined by 49,000 to 1.45 million last
year, and there were 164,000 hit-and-run accidents, compared with
188,000 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
CBS attributed the sharp drop in crime to an increase in
anti-theft measures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
