<HEADLINE> Belgium Denies Tax Info Exchange with Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Belgium does not plan to
provide information to the Netherlands on interest earned on
Belgian-based bank accounts, a Belgian finance ministry spokesman
was quoted by Thursday's Dutch daily newspaper Het Financieele
Dagblad as saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that talks are being held on a new tax
treaty between the two countries, but that the data exchange issue
has been scrapped from the agenda.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Dutch finance minister Gerrit Zalm has told
parliament that Dutch and Belgian taxation authorities were
examining ways to provide automatic access to each other's tax
data, including information on bank accounts. The Dutch finance
ministry said on Wednesday it had nothing to add to Zalm's
statement of the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Zalm's comments were made after Dutch parliament members
questioned a recent advertisement by Belgian bank Kredit aan de
Nijverheid, part of the Dutch-Belgian Fortis Group, calling on
Dutch savers to deposit their money in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Zalm told parliament Dutch banks had already agreed to refrain
from cross-border advertising in order not to encourage tax
evasion and that he had asked Fortis to apply the agreement to its
foreign subsidiaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
