<HEADLINE> Egypt to Offer Aid to Refugees in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will offer material
assistance to the refugees in Zambia, who have been driven out of
their countries by civil wars, Egyptian Education Minister Hussein
Bahaa Eddine said today.
</P>
<P>
Eddin told reporters that President Hosni Mubarak received a
message from Zambian President Frederich Chiluba earlier today on
the present events in the Great Lakes area, which was delivered
by Zambian Education Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye who is
currently visiting here.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Chiluba asked Egypt for help in settling its
unsolved problems represented by the daily flow of about 500
refugees since last year from Rwanda and Zaire, the Egyptian MENA
news agency quoted the Zambian official as saying after meeting
with Eddine today.
</P>
<P>
This situation has negatively affected Zambia's economy and
Zambia is looking forward to Egypt's interference in helping the
country through diplomatic channels besides its material
assistance, Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Zairians have flocked into neighboring Zambia and
Tanzania in search of shelter, after a civil war led by ethnic
Tutsis in eastern Zaire broke out last September. Many face
starvation in refugee camps with terrible living conditions.
</P>
<P>
Burundi, Rwanda, Zaire, Uganda and Tanzania, known as the Great
Lakes area of Africa, have been involved in other rising
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
These conflicts have resulted in millions of refugees and
displaced people.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been seeking a settlement to the conflicts of the
African countries within the framework of the Organization of
African Unity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
