<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Angola is set to spend 21
million U.S. Dollars to disarm nearly 100,000 grown-up fighters
of the once warring parties in the five-month period starting from
March 1.
</P>
<P>
The joint committee overseeing Angola's peace process approved
here today a plan on quick demobilization of adult servicemen
around the southern African country, said U.N. Envoy to Angola
Blondin Beye.
</P>
<P>
The top challenge facing the plan is how to have the
opposition National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) join the formation of the united army, Beye noted.
</P>
<P>
Without the involvement of UNITA, the plan will be impossible
to be carried out, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added the Angolan government has passed a budget to ensure
adequate money for the demobilization.
</P>
<P>
As many as 2,029 child fighters in the country have so far
been disarmed and returned to civil lives since last September
and the work will continue, said Beye. enditem

