<HEADLINE> Islamic militant Killed in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Security forces today killed a
suspected Muslim extremist who took part in last week's attack on
a Coptic church in southern Egypt, Egyptian MENA news agency
quoted security sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
A security campaign also arrested nine suspected criminals in
Abu Qorqas, in Minya, 240 kilometers south of Cairo, where gunmen
opened fire indiscriminately last Wednesday night at the Mary
Girgis Church, killing nine Copts and injuring six others.
</P>
<P>
The militant involved in the church attack, Ahmed Ali ahmed
Sayyed, was holed up in a sugar cane plantation in the nearby
township of Malawi before he was killed by the the security men
who stormed the area, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Two farmers sustained gunshot wounds in the crossfire between
security forces and the militant and died later in hospital, the
source added.
</P>
<P>
MENA said in an earlier report that the police have identified
the six militants involved in the church attacks in southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The militants have waged a violent campaign to establish a
strict Islamic state since 1992. More than 1,050 people have been
killed in the clashes, most of them civilians and police in the
south.
</P>
<P>
In a predominantly Muslim country, Copts make up about 10
percent of Egypt's 60 million population. 
</P>
