<HEADLINE> Major European Stocks Down on Wall Street's Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 20 (Xinhua) -- All major stock markets in
Europe ended lower today, depressed by the Dow's decline and a
softer dollar, with Frankfurt suffering the most losses.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index on the London market ended little changed
after a faltering Dow Jones pulled it back from a new record high
of 4,362.4, hit in morning trade, to close 1.3 points down at
4,356.1.
</P>
<P>
Share prices in Frankfurt were also dragged down by a slump in
bonds on the much higher-than-expected M3 money supply data for
January, with the DAX-30 index 37.72 points lower at 3,196.03.
</P>
<P>
M3 grew at an annualized 11.7 percent, compared to a 7.9
percent December rise.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market was also depressed by a softer
dollar and Wall Street's overnight losses.
</P>
<P>
Weaker bond prices and another fall on Wall Street as well as a
market consolidation following recent strong gains kept share
prices in Paris in negative territories, though stocks finished
off their lows, with the CAC-40 index 19.52 points down at
2,575.24.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended down
1.3 points at 4,356.1. The Frankfurt DAX-40 index closed 37.72
points weaker at 3,196.03. In Paris, the CAC-40 index finished
down 19.52 points at 2,575.24. 
</P>
