<HEADLINE> Spain's Trade Up with African Portuguese-Speaking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Spain's two-way trade with
four of the five Portuguese-speaking countries in Africa shot up
in the first 11 months of 1996 over the same period of 1995,
the Angolan Information Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The exports to Spain from Angola, Mozambique, Sao Tome &AMP;
Principe and Cape Verde rose by 76.12 percent, two percent, 4.6
times and 25 times respectively, to about 209 million, 40.1
million, 903,000 and nearly 840,000 U.S. Dollars, during the
period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Guinea-Bissau's exports to Spain fell by 31.2
percent to 25.76 million Dollars and its imports from Spain
soared by 4.7 percent to 4.3 million Dollars, the report quoted
Spain's official data as saying.
</P>
<P>
Between January and November in 1996, Angola and Mozambique
imported goods separately worth 82 and 11.2 million Dollars from
Spain, up 48.6 and 29.5 percent compared with the same period of
1995.
</P>
<P>
The imports from Spain by the island states of Cape Verde and
Sao Tome &AMP; Principe went up respectively by nine and two percent
to 4.76 million and 621,000 Dollars in the period, said the
report. enditem

