<HEADLINE> Canada's Retail Sales Drop Slightly in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in Canada dipped
0.3 percent in December after three months of strong growth,
Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
Four of seven trade sectors saw increases in retail sales in
the month. Growth was the strongest in drug stores, followed by
clothing and food. Losses in general merchandise and furniture
offset the gains.
</P>
<P>
Despite the drop in December, retail sales in the last two
months of the year went up to 27.4 billion U.S. dollars, about 4.5
percent more than in the last two Christmas seasons, the federal
fact-gathering agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the whole of 1996, Canadian retailers achieved a growth of
2.4 percent, 0.1 percent higher than that of 1995, the agency
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
