<HEADLINE> Nepal to Receive Continued ADB Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Nepal is to receive
financial assistance of about 80-90 million U.S. dollars annually
from the Asian Development Bank (ADB) in the next few years up to
2000, according to the bank today.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ADB will also provide technical assistance
grants totaling about 5 million dollars every year to Nepal, an
official of the bank told a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
These amounts would not include any ADB loans supporting
large-sized hydropower projects in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Under a three-year cycle program, the ADB will provide
financial support to three projects in Nepal every year up to
2000, ADB program manager in Nepal Yoshihiro Iwasaki said.
</P>
<P>
For 1997, a total of 110 million dollars have been earmarked
for three projects on community groundwater irrigation, airport
improvement and agriculture program respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB official said the bank will assist Nepal in the next
three years in achieving its goals in areas of debenture market,
road improvement, human resources development, tourism and poverty
alleviation.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for Nepal to pay attention to
clearing hurdles caused by the absence of infrastructures and
policy improvement as the country has not been able to attract
foreign investment compared with other Asian countries.  
</P>
