<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Military Dialogue in Cyprus: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. official has said that
progress has been made in the indirect military dialog between the
Cypriot National Guard and the Turkish forces in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Waldemar Rokozewski, spokesman of UN the Peace-Keeping Force in
Cyprus (UNFICYP) said today that after months of stalled
deliberations, certain progress has been made quite recently in
the talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
he said, "we are more optimistic. We believe that negotiations
may bring positive results on the entire package, proposed by the
U.N.".
</P>
<P>
UNFICYP is sponsoring separate talks with the National Guard
and the Turkish forces over a package of measures, which
include the extension of the 1989 unmanning agreement, the
prohibition of loaded weapons along the buffer zone and a code
of conduct for soldiers. The talks have been dragging on for
months.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the U.N. decided to step up its contacts from
once to twice a week in an effort to achieve some progress
after both community leaders gave their support to the dialog.
</P>
<P>
Rokozewski said UNFICYP welcomed the progress and would like
to conclude with the entire package as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He added that since all the elements are well known to
the parties concerned, "we believe that we can do it very
fast. Recent negotiations which we had with both sides showed
an opportunity for an agreement to be concluded."
</P>
<P>
The indirect talks between the Greek Cypriot National Guard
and Turkish forces, under the U.N. auspices, was conducted
following a tension along the 180-kilometers demarcation line,
which partitions this east Mediterranean island into two parts.
</P>
<P>
Since last June, four unarmed Greek Cypriots have been
killed and a Turkish soldier was mysteriously murdered along the
buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived military coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
