<HEADLINE> Conference on Reporting China to Outside World (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The main task of reporting
China to the outside world in 1997 is to bring a better
understanding of the country to others, according to a leading
press official.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Jianhui, Director of the International Communication
Office of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee,
made the remark at a national conference on reporting China to the
outside world, which was held in Beijing from February 17-21.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, also Director of the Information Office of the State
Council, said the upcoming Party congress is of great historic
importance and the international community pays close attention to
it.
</P>
<P>
The reporting of China to the outside world should fully
reflect the historic achievement of the country's reform and
opening-up under the leadership of the CPC, he said.
</P>
<P>
Such reports should also make clear that as long as China
sticks to the socialist road while retaining its unique Chinese
characteristics, the country will continue to make notable
progress in social development and have an even more promising
future.
</P>
<P>
A stable political situation, consistent policies and a stable
society can only help prove that the CPC is capable of getting
China's overall situation under control, which will win the
support of the people of all ethnic groups, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
The just-ended conference focused on the further research of
economic development, the convening of the 15th National Congress
of the CPC, and the resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed how to strengthen reportage,
increase the understanding of China by people outside the country,
improve China's international image and create a sound
international press environment for China's reforms and the
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
During and prior to the meeting, Premier Li Peng and Ding
Guangen, member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee and Head of the Propaganda Department, met with the
participants.
