<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU's Industrial Production Up 0.3 Percent Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's (EU)
industrial production was 0.3 percent up last year, according to
estimates published today by EU's statistical office Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
The annual industrial growth, calculated with production
indexes for total industry available up to last November, was a
much weaker rate compared with 1995's average rise of 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics available from Eurostat indicated that
the Netherlands showed the best results with a 4.4 percent growth
in 1996, nearly doubling the 2.4 percent rise in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Finland and Sweden registered growth rates of 2.3
percent and 2.1 percent respectively, much lower than their 7.5
percent and 10.0 percent increases in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Germany and France recorded weak growths of 0.2
percent, 0.3 percent and 0.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Even worse than their EU neighbors, Italy, Spain and
Luxembourg's industrial production reported minus growth rates of
0.23 percent, 0.9 percent and 0.9 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
For Ireland and Austria, Eurostat said, there were not enough
data for reliable estimates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
