<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mideast Role Supportive With Israelis, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States plays a
"supportive role with the Israelis" in the Mideast peace
negotiations, U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Edward Walker said.
</P>
<P>
This could be the first time that the U.S. side, a key mediator
in the peace process, concedes that it stands by Israel in the
process, observers here noted.
</P>
<P>
Walker made the remarks during an interview published in the
latest issue of local English language Al-Ahram Weekly that
focused mainly on the agenda of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
visit to Washington, due to begin on March 10.
</P>
<P>
When speaking of the Egyptian and U.S. roles in the peace
process, Walker told the Weekly, "We would make a mistake to
think (the roles of the two countries were identical), and we
would not be very effective, if we had identical roles."
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of the Camp David peace agreement in 1978,
it had become clear that Egypt "has an obligation and a role to
play with the Palestinians, that is supportive role, one which is
designed to help them to reach an agreement," he continued.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., on the other hand, plays a "supportive role with
the Israelis," also to help them to arrive at an accord, the
U.S. diplomat asserted.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, "there is a slightly different cast on
each and we believe that both of us, acting together can help
mediate the problems between the two sides and encourage the two
sides, and I think that's what happened....It's important to
maintain the dialog."
</P>
<P>
Talking about Mubarak's coming trip to Washington, Walker said
that the timing of the tour is "good," the aim of which is to talk
on "very difficult areas" of the Palestinian track of the peace
process, according to the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said that the Egyptian-U.S. economic
partnership will also be on the agenda of Mubarak's trip with his
counterpart Bill Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
