<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping's Great, Brilliant Life (20) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In targeting the old sytem that was handicapping productivity,
Deng proposed that reform is the only way for China to develop
productivity, noting that reform was significant to the liberation
of productivity. "Reform is China's second revolution," he
commented.
</P>
<P>
Deng gave his full support to rural reforms that started by
fixing farm quotas for each household. Summerizing the experiences
of rural reforms, he shifted the reforms to urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The Third Plenary Session of the 12th Central Committee made a
decision on restructuring the economy in 1984 that involved
reforms on the economic, political, scientific, technological and
educational sectors in China. Deng spoke highly of the decision.
</P>
<P>
Facing this unprecedented and complicated experiment, Deng put
forward a guiding principle of great courage and cautious
steps. He said, "We must stick to two principles consistently. One
is socialist public ownership forming the mainstay of the economy
and the other is common prosperity."
</P>
<P>
He broke with the traditional concepts and tied the market
economy to socialism. In many of his speeches from 1979 to 1992,
Deng pointed out that socialism should also have a market
economy. Both planning and market are the means, he said, but not
the intrinsic difference between socialism and capitalism. These
speeches laid a theoretical foundation for the Party to set the
reform targets for a socialist market economic structure.
</P>
<P>
In 1980, Deng made an important speech entitled "Reform of the
Party and the State leadership structure" at an enlarged meeting
of the Party's Political Bureau. His speech targeted the
fundamental and long-term problems of leadership and organization
structure and gave a summary of experiences and lessons of the
"Cultural Revolution".
</P>
<P>
Deng called for a reform of the bad practices in the existing
leadership structure. He noted in 1986 that without reforming the
political system, the economic reform would be hampered and the
development of productivity checked. He made it clear that the
goal of the reform of the political structure was maintaining the
vitality of the Party and the State and making leading officials
at all levels younger, getting rid of the bureaucracy, increasing
work efficiency, and mobilizing the enthusiasm of the grass roots
and the people.
</P>
<P>
Deng stressed that China must work hard to develop socialist
democracy, strengthen the socialist legal system, and build
socialist democracy in the process of socialist modernization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
