<HEADLINE> Australian PM Attacks Racism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard strongly attacked the manifestations of racism while
addressing a party in Chinatown in Sydney tonight.
</P>
<P>
Attending the annual Chinese new year dinner, the prime
minister praised the Chinese community for its entrepreneurs and
contribution to the Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
"Of course," he said, "there are some within our ranks who
harbor prejudice and bigotry and who do display intolerance,
whether it is on ethnic or racial grounds or other grounds. And I
want to say, that is not part of the true Australian spirit."
</P>
<P>
"Any manifestation of racism in our ranks is repugnant to
everything for which Australia has always stood."
</P>
<P>
Howard's comments were directed against last year's racial
debate sparked by Queensland MP Pauline Hanson who said Asians
formed ghettoes and Australia was in danger of becoming swamped by
migrants.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Australia's relations with China, Howard said he
would travel to China "with a determination to further build a
pragmatic, common-sense relationship built on mutual respect and
on a recognition of the importance of welcoming China into the
family of nations, into the Asia Pacific region. It's on that
basis that I will visit Beijing and Shanghai during Easter of this
year."  
</P>
</TEXT>
