<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Forfeit W. Bank Education Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to forfeit a
100-million-US-Dollar World Bank loan to its primary education
for poor project performances, the Guardian paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said because of the poor showing of local
authorities in implementing the project, the talk on another
80-million-Dollar loan to secondary education which started in
1995 is also jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
It quoted authoritative sources at the World Bank mission in
Nigeria as saying that the bank has already notified the Nigerian
Finance Ministry of its resolve to cancel 100 million Dollars of
the 120 million Dollars granted in 1991.
</P>
<P>
It said Nigeria's National Primary Education Commission (NPEC)
has applied through the finance ministry for the extending of the
project for another three years, as the original project is
expected to terminate in June this year.
</P>
<P>
But a World Bank official reportedly said on Thursday, "the
chances are very slim that we will extend the loan duration."
</P>
<P>
The report blamed the impending cancellation of the project to
the massive fraud uncovered within NPEC, which has been
responsible for the implementation of the project.
</P>
<P>
"If such magnitude of fraud existed at NPEC which the World
Bank thinks is the only organ that could creditably implement the
World Bank project, which agency then can the bank entrust with
the duty," a source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
