<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian, Eastern European Leaders Mourn Deng's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian and Eastern European
leaders on Thursday expressed sorrow over the death of Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping and praised him for his great contributions
to China's opening-up and reform process.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin sent a letter of condolences to
his Chinese counterpart Jiang Zemin, describing Deng, who died
late on Wednesday at the age of 93, as "an outstanding statesman."
</P>
<P>
Deng was the architect of China's reforms which have brought
historic changes to the country, Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's State Duma (lower house of parliament) observed a
minute's silence to mourn Deng when it convened on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
State Duma Chairman Gennady Seleznev said Deng's death will not
lead to a change in China's economic policy, adding that "the
Chinese leaders will stick to the policy with full confidence."
</P>
<P>
Uzbek President Islam Karimov and Lithuanian President Algirdas
Brazauskas, currently visiting Uzbekistan, both expressed sorrow
over Deng's death at a joint press conference on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Karimov described Deng as "one of the greatest leaders of the
world in the 20th century", "the general architect and helmsman of
China's economic reforms."
</P>
<P>
He said, "Deng drafted China's reform and opening-up policies,
under which the country has gained splendid achievements in
economic development.
</P>
<P>
"It was a great contribution of Deng to enable 1.2 billion
Chinese people to be well-fed and well-clothed."
</P>
<P>
Brazauskas said Deng was a great and intelligent statesman, and
that it was worthwhile to learn from Deng's model of economic
reform and his successful experience in establishing special
economic zones.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma, in a telegram sent to Jiang
Zemin on Thursday, hailed Deng as "an outstanding politician of
the age" and "architect of China's reforms."
</P>
<P>
Deng enjoyed a high reputation worldwide through promoting
international relations based on equality, and mutual respect for
sovereignty and independence, said Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian President Alexandr Lukashenko went to the Chinese
mission in Minsk Thursday to mourn the death of Deng, describing
him as a "brilliant statesman and politician," adding that Belarus
will learn from China, especially in social and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian President Petar Stoiannov visited the Chinese Embassy
in Sofia to express sorrow over the death of Deng, saying that
Deng was one of the greatest statesmen of the century and his
death was "a great loss for the Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Foreign Minister Kovacs Laszlo said on Thursday
during a visit to Poland that Deng was one of the most influential
leaders in China's modern history.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Zoran Lilic said in his telegram of
condolence to Jiang Zemin on Thursday that Deng had left behind
him work of lasting value, in launching reforms in Chinese
society, in constructing a model of socialism with Chinese
characteristics, and in creating conditions for the country's
unification with the concept of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
Albania on Thursday regretted the "great loss of the great
Chinese people, China and its friends across the world".
</P>
<P>
Macedonia also expressed deep sorrow over the death of "China's
architect" and "one of the most renowned activists of the 20th
century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Oks Use of Video in Soccer Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- World soccer ruling body FIFA
said on Friday it had approved the use of video replays in a
friendly match between France and Sweden in April.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, made by the French Football Association, must
also be approved by the International Football Board, which
controls the laws of the game, when it meets next week in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
"The French FA has offically asked if it can experiment with
video and we said OK," said FIFA spokesman Andreas Herren. "But
the International Football Board will have to give its OK before
any video cameras can be used." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
