<HEADLINE> Singapore PM to Visit Four African Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong will make his first official visit to South Africa,
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Botswana from February 25 to March 5, the
Prime Minister's Office announced today.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will be accompanied on the trip by Mrs. Goh,
Minister for National Development and Second Minister for foreign
Affairs Lim Hng Kiang, Minister of State for Law and Home Affairs
Ho Peng Kee and other senior government officials, it said.
</P>
<P>
A 40-member business delegation will also be accompanying the
prime minister on the four-nation tour.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, Goh will meet with President Nelson Mandela,
Executive Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and leaders of the main
political parties there.
</P>
<P>
In Johannesburg, Goh will deliver a keynote speech to the
African-Asian Society.
</P>
<P>
He will be in Zimbabwe between February 28 and March 2 where he
will meet with President Robert Mugabe and visit the Victoria
Falls.
</P>
<P>
In Namibia, Goh will meet with President Sam Nujoma and visit
Walvis Bay and the Export Processing Zone there.
</P>
<P>
His last stop is Botswana where he will call on President
Ketumile Masire. He will also have an informal dialogue on
Singapore's developmental experience at the University of
Botswana.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
