<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Kicks off Year of Heritage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The Year of Heritage, the
first year-round event dedicated to the promotion of local
heritage preservation, was kicked off today in Hong Kong, whose
6,000 years of civilization seem to be eclipsed by her status as
an industrial and financial hub.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Antiquities Advisory Board (AAB), the Lord
Wilson Heritage Trust and the Antiquities and Monuments Office,
the Year of Heritage program will present exhibitions, tours,
lectures, archaeological workshops and international conference on
heritage education, among other events.
</P>
<P>
AAB Chairman David Lung Ping-yee expected that the program
would "arouse public awareness and concern of local heritage
preservation and help the younger generation increase their
understanding of and love for the rich cultural heritage that we
own."
</P>
<P>
With Hong Kong's return to China in mid-1997, HK has become the
focus of global media, and the Year of Heritage provides a golden
opportunity to publicize Hong Kong's heritage, he said.
</P>
<P>
Archaeological studies in Hong Kong have uncovered evidence of
ancient human activities, dating back to over 6,000 years ago, at
many sites along the winding shoreline.
</P>
<P>
Chief Secretary Anson Chan officiated at the opening ceremony
at Charter Garden, Central.
</P>
<P>
If the heritage disappeared one day from the territory, Hong
Kong would be a rootless city whatever progress was achieved (in
other fields), she noted.
</P>
<P>
Prizes were awarded to the winners and merits of the logo
design competition for the Year of Heritage.
</P>
<P>
A variety show of Hong Kong's treasures was also staged at the
ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
