<HEADLINE> Nigeria Restates Commitment to Peaceful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Head of State General Sani
Abacha has restated Nigeria's commitment to the peaceful
resolution of the Bakassi dispute, the Daily Times paper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
a peaceful resolution of the dispute would advance the cause
of peace, stability, solidarity and progress of the entire
continent, he said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Abacha reportedly made the comment in Abuja while receiving
Lamine Kamara, Guinean Foreign Minister and special envoy of
Guinean President Lansana Conte.
</P>
<P>
President Conte has been mandated by the United Nations to
intervene in the conflict between Nigerian and Cameroun over the
oil-rich Bakassi peninsula in the Gulf of Guinea. The two
countries have gone into clashes for several times in the few
last years.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Head of State is of the view that the persistence
and escalation of the crisis would not serve any useful purpose,
and that the earlier the conflict is resolved, the better for all
parties concerned, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Abacha also expressed confidence in the ability, sincerity and
experience of President Conte in meeting the U.N. mission, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
