<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading British newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The British government's gun control legislation, the
Firearms (Amendment) Bill, cleared its final parliamentary hurdle
Thursday night after pro-shooting peers gave up further opposition
to the measure.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Britain's Labor Party Thursday gave details of its planned
reforms of the House of Lords. The party said it would appoint new
members in proportion to the national vote in the general election
once it had abolished voting rights for hereditary peers.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- Germany's vast economic problems have driven Chancellor
Helmut Kohl into the embrace of the opposition, opening the way to
a grand coalition in all but name.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- A sharp fall in the number of school-leavers and
undergraduates wanting to become teachers in Britain was revealed
Thursday, fueling concern about an impending shortage of qualified
staff.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- The Labor Party moved to close the gap with the Tories over
a single currency Thursday night by giving the strongest
indication yet that it did not envisage Britain being in the first
wave of monetary union in 1999. 
</P>
