<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping's Great, Brilliant Life (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Huaihai Campaign began in November 1948. The CPC Central
Committee and the Central Commission decided that Liu Bocheng,
Chen Yi, Deng Xiaoping, Su Yu, and Tan Zhenlin form the General
Front Committee, with Deng acting as secretary, exercising unified
command over the Central China Plains Field Army (later the Second
Field Army) and the East China Field Army (later the Third Field
Army).
</P>
<P>
During the Huaihai Campaign, Chiang Kai-shek deployed nearly
800,000 troops, while the PLA soldiers numbered only 600,000. In
terms of weapon and equipment, the Kuomintang troops had an even
greater advantage.
</P>
<P>
The General Front Committee carried out the principle of
concentrating superior forces and wiping out the enemy one by one,
with the result that the PLA eliminated 555,000 enemy troops in 66
days of fighting, winning complete victory in the Huaihai Campaign.
</P>
<P>
In March 1949, Deng attended the Second Plenum of the Seventh
CPC Central Committee and according to an appointment, he also
served as first secretary of the East China Bureau. On April 21,
on the order to march nationwide issued by Chairman Mao Zedong and
Commander-In-Chief Zhu De, the General Front Committee, with Deng
as its secretary, led the second and third field armies to launch
the Nanjing-Shanghai-Hangzhou Campaign. The PLA troops broke
through the Yangtze River defense of the Kuomintang troops in one
stroke, triumphantly crossed the Yangtze River, and liberated
Nanjing, Shanghai, and large areas in Jiangsu, Anhui, Zhejiang,
and Jiangxi provinces. The liberation of Nanjing meant the
downfall of the Kuomintang's reactionary rule.
</P>
<P>
In September 1949, on the eve of the founding of the People's
Republic of China, Deng was elected a member of the Central
People's Government at the First Plenum of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
In October, he served as a member of the Chinese People's
Revolutionary Military Commission. Later, he and Liu Bocheng led
troops toward the southwest, rapidly eliminating more than 900,000
Kuomintang reactionary troops entrenched in Yunnan, Guizhou, and
Sichuan provinces and driving the Kuomintang's reactionaries out
of the mainland.
</P>
<P>
In southwest China, Deng served as the first secretary of the
Southwest China Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, vice-chairman
of the Southwest China Military and Administrative Committee, and
political commissar of the Southwest China Military Command.
</P>
<P>
While commanding troops along with Liu Bocheng and He Long in
removing bandits and remaining enemy forces, Deng worked on
uniting all those who could be united and winning over all those
within the enemy camp who could be won over, thereby bringing all
positive factors into play, clearing up various ethnic
estrangements left over from history prudently and steadily, and
promoting unity among various ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Deng also mobilized and relied on people to accomplish the
tasks of land and other social reform, strengthening political
power at various levels, rapidly restoring industrial and
agricultural production and building the Chengdu-Chongqing
Railway, thereby promptly settling the chaotic situation there and
creating a new mood of stability and development in southwest
China. He also participated in leading troops to Tibet and
liberate it by peaceful means, thus realizing the complete
liberation of the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0143 </DOCNO>
