</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping's Great, Brilliant Life (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In July, 1952, Deng was transferred to Beijing and appointed
vice-premier of the Government Administration Council and deputy
director of the Financial and Economic Committee, as well as
director of the communications office of the Government
Administration Council and minister of Finance. He suggested that
the country's finance should be placed on a constant, stable and
reliable basis and should be guided by an all-sided concept.
</P>
<P>
In 1954, he served as secretary-general of the CPC Central
Committee, head of the Organization Department of the CPC Central
Committee, vice-premier of the State Council, and vice-chairman of
the National Defence Council. He made an important contribution in
the struggle against attempts to split the Party and usurp the
supreme power of the State and the Party by Gao Gang and Rao
Shushi.
</P>
<P>
In April, 1955, Deng was elected to the Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee at the 5th Plenary Session of the 7th CPC
Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
In September, 1956, in his report on revising the Party's
Constitution at the 8th CPC National Congress, he elaborated on
the ruling Party's task in strengthening itself, pointing out that
the the Party faces new challenges, and it is necessary to
constantly guard against being divorced from the masses and
losing contact with reality, and called on the Party to adhere to
the mass line and democratic centralism, enhance the collective
leadership of Party organizations at various levels and avoid
arbitrary individual act in making decisions on major issues.
</P>
<P>
Deng was elected member of the Standing Committee of the
Politburo and general-secretary of the CPC Central Committee at
the 1st Plenary Session of the 8th CPC Central Committee to become
an important member of the first-generation leadership of the
Communist Party of China with Mao Zedong at its core.
</P>
<P>
In recommending Deng for the post of the general secretary of
the CPC Central Committee, Mao said that he was an able,
thoughtful, fair, and honest man who took the views of all into
account. In 1959, he was again made member of the Standing
Committee of the Central Military Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portuguese President to Visit Beijing as Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese President Jorge
Sampaio will start his visit to China from February 23 as
scheduled although part of his visit itineraries may be slightly
adjusted, said a top Chinese official here today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch,
told reporters after a meeting with the Portuguese president for
one hour twenty minutes that the president's visit to China will
start as scheduled although the Chinese people are all in deep
sorrow over Deng Xiaoping's pass-away.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government welcomes the scheduled visit of
Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio from February 23, although its
1.2 billion people are in deep grief over the loss of a great
leader," said Wang. "Some itineraries may be slightly adjusted,
but the substantive talks between leaders of the two countries
will be held as planned."
</P>
<P>
Sampaio canceled his planned visit on Thursday here and made an
announcement of condolence over Deng's pass-away. He also paid his
last respect to the late Chinese leader at a mourning hall in the
Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Wang today, the president again
expressed his grief over the death of an outstanding Chinese
leader. Wang thanked him on behalf of the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
"(The president's move) not only shows the president's respect
to a great man of the century, it also demonstrates that the
president highly values the friendship between China and
Portugal," said the director.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time Sampaio visited Macao after he took office
as Portuguese president in March last year.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to discuss a wide range of issues concerning the
transition of Macao and Sino-Portuguese political, economic and
trade relations with Chinese leaders during his forthcoming visit
to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
China and Portugal have maintained good relations following the
establishment of diplomatic relations in 1979. Under the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao signed
in 1987, China will resume its exercise of sovereignty over Macao
as of December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Macao will enjoy a high degree of autonomy after 1999. The
current life style and its capitalist system will remain unchanged
for 50 years, according to the joint declaration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
