</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping's Brilliant Life (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Because of the difficulties of life in France, Deng had to work
in several factories after studying in a high school only for
several months, where he experienced the hardships of life and was
bitterly exploited by the capitalists. During that period, he and
a group of other Chinese students with progressive ideas began to
believe in Marxism and became revolutionaries, having been
influenced by the October Socialist Revolution in Russia.
</P>
<P>
In 1922, he joined the Chinese Youth Communist Party in Europe
(later renamed the European branch of the Chinese Socialist Youth
League), and in 1924 became a member of the Chinese Communist
Party. From that time on, he became a professional proletarian
revolutionary and a communist fighter.
</P>
<P>
He served as a leading member of the Youth League's general
branch in Europe and a special commissioner of the Chinese
Communist Party to the Leon region. He also took the position of
editor of the Youth League's magazine, "The Red Light".
</P>
<P>
In early 1926, Deng left France for the Soviet Union, where he
studied at the Institute of the Peoples of the East and in the
Name of Sun Yat-sen. In his autobiography of that time he wrote,
"If I stay in Russia for only a day, I will study hard for a day,
so that I can understand Communism well," and "As soon as I
arrived in Moscow, I made up my mind to give my body to our Party,
and to our class."
</P>
<P>
In the Spring of 1927, Deng was ordered by the Party to return
to China, where he served as chief of the Political Division and a
political instructor at the Zhongshan Military School in Xi'an of
the National Allied Army under Feng Yuxiang's command, while also
serving as secretary of the Communist Party organization in the
school.
</P>
<P>
When Chiang Kai-shek staged the April 12 counter-revolutionary
coup d'etat in Shanghai, Deng went to Hankou sometime between June
and July and worked in the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping's Great, Brilliant Life (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Not long after that, the Wuhan Government under Wang Jingwei
openly turned against the Communists. The nation was under the
"white" terror and the Chinese Communist Party was forced to go
underground. In response to the circumstances, Deng changed his
name to Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
On August 7 he attended an emergency meeting of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee (known as the August 7 Meeting),
which repudiated and rectified the "right capitulationism"
advocated by Chen Duxiu and which set down the general policy of
starting an agrarian revolution and staging armed struggles
against the Kuomintang reactionaries. Towards the end of that
year, he moved with the offices of the CPC Central Committee
secretly to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
From 1928 to 1929, he served as secretary general of the CPC
Central Committee. In 1928, when the CPC was holding its Sixth
National Congress in Moscow, he helped those CPC Central Committee
leaders who had stayed in China to arrange the daily work of the
CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
After the failure of the great revolution in 1927, the Chinese
Communist Party staged a series of armed uprisings in order to
save the revolution. In the summer of 1929, as the CPC Central
Committee representative, Deng went to Guangxi province to lead an
uprising.
</P>
<P>
Using the name Deng Bin, he served as secretary of the Guangxi
Front Committee of the CPC. Along with Zhang Yunyi and others he
staged the Baise Uprising in December, created the 7th Red Army,
and established the Youjiang Revolutionary Base.
</P>
<P>
In February of the following year, he launched the Longzhou
Uprising, formed the 8th Red Army, and established the Zuojiang
Revolutionary Base. In the process he became political commissar
and secretary of the Front Committee.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of Deng Xiaoping and others, the number of
Red Army soldiers grew to 7,000 in about four months, and the
areas under their control grew to more than 20 counties and some
one million people, believed to be one of the bigger revolutionary
bases at the time.
</P>
<P>
But because of the influence of the erroneous "left adventurism"
in the Party, the troops experienced a series of setbacks in
battles and had to trek 3,500 kilometers to join the main Red Army
in the area of the Jiangxi Central Revolutionary Base.
</P>
<P>
Deng had put forward ideas opposing the erroneous "Left"
command methods, but they were not adopted. In February 1931, he
was sent by the Front Committee to report on their work to the CPC
Central Committee in Shanghai. During this period, he wrote the
"Work Report of the 7th Army", explaining the 7th Army's situation
in detail and summing up the experiences before and after the
uprising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Approves Privatization of Manila Waterworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today approved the privatization of the Manila water service
system worth 7 billion U.S. dollars, the largest of its kind in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Under the recommendation of the Committee on Privatization,
Ramos endorsed the project won by two local firms, the
Presidential Office said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The approval came after the Court of Appeals lifted a temporary
restraining order it issued last month to freeze the privatization
of the water supply and sewerage system in the capital region.
</P>
<P>
To improve efficiency of the water system in Manila, the
government chose to privatize the Metropolitan Water Supply and
Sewerage System (MWSS). Under concessional agreements, the MWSS
will be turned over to the two winning bidders in June.
</P>
<P>
Public Works and Highways Secretary Gregorio Vigilar hailed the
lifting of the court order and today's approval, saying it would
create a more favorable perception by foreign investors of the
country's investment climate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping's Great, Brilliant Life (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the summer of 1931, Deng arrived in the Central
Revolutionary Base in Jiangxi, and served successively as
secretary of the CPC Ruijin County Committee, secretary of the CPC
Central County Committee of Huichang, and head of the Propaganda
Department of the CPC Jiangxi Provincial Committee.
</P>
<P>
At that time, the Provisional CPC Central Committee, which
pursued "Left adventurism", moved from Shanghai to the Central
Revolutionary Base. Deng along with Mao Zetan, Xie Weijun, Gu Bo,
and others persevered in proceeding from specific conditions and
followed the correct political line as represented by Mao Zedong.
</P>
<P>
They opposed the theory of taking cities as the revolutionary
center, and held that the revolutionary force should develop in
the vast rural area where the enemy's power was relatively
weak. They were against military adventurism, and advocated luring
the enemy in deep, and opposed the practice of expanding the main
force of the Red Army by weakening local armed forces, and stood
for equal emphasis be placed on the development of both
forces. They also spoke out against the "Left" policy of land
distribution.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional CPC Central Committee launched a struggle
against the above-mentioned four men, and Deng was stripped of his
position as head of the Provincial Party Committee, given a
serious disciplinary punishment and a warning inside the Party,
and sent to the outlying county of Le'an to serve as an inspector
of the CPC Nancun District Committee. This was the first wrongful
disciplinary punishment he had suffered in his political life in
the Party.
</P>
<P>
Later, with the support of Wang Jiaxiang, director of the
General Political Department of the Central Military Commission,
and other people, he was transferred to the General Political
Department to serve as secretary general. Shortly afterwards, he
was in charge of the Red Star News, the Department's paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng Xiaoping's Great, Brilliant Life (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Proceeding from specific conditions, he published a number of
articles and delivered speeches on "The Party and The
Anti-Japanese Democratic Political Power", "Principles, Tasks, and
Orientation of Efforts in Cultural Work of The 129th Division", "A
Outlined Summary of The Struggle Against The Enemy During the Past
Five Years", "Economic Construction of The Taihang Mountain Area",
and "Speech at The Mobilization Meeting for The Rectification
Movement at The Party School of The Northern Bureau of the CPC
Central Committee".
</P>
<P>
In these articles and speeches, he proposed a series of
policies and tactics for the struggle against the enemy, and set
forth the principles of accumulating strength to prepare for the
strategic counterattack and the founding of the New China in the
post-war period.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at a mobilization meeting for the Rectification
Movement at the Party school of the Northern Bureau of the CPC
Central Committee, he pointed out that Mao Zedong thought is
Marxism-Leninism with Chinese characteristics and should become
the Party's guide.
</P>
<P>
In June of 1945, Deng was elected a member of the CPC Central
Committee at the Party's Seventh National Congress. When Japan
surrendered in August, the four base areas that he and Liu Bocheng
founded in north China -- the Taihang, Taiyue, South Hebei, and
Hebei-Shandong-Henan -- were basically linked with each other, and
became the largest liberated area in the country, an area of 24
million people and 300,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Also in August, the CPC Central Committee decided to set up the
Shanxi-Hebei-Shandong-Henan Bureau of the CPC Central Committee
and the Shanxi-Hebei-Shandong-Henan Military Region. Deng became
secretary of the Bureau and political commissar of the Military
Region, with Liu Bocheng as commander-in-chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
