<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Income Tax Law Comes into Effect in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 21 (Xinhua) -- New income tax law comes into
effect this week in Vietnam, raising the threshold for both
Vietnamese citizens and foreigners classified as residents, as
well as abolishing tax on gifts remitted to the Vietnamese
citizens from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Local press quoted deputy Finance Minister Nguyen Thi Kim Ngan
as saying that the much-criticized irregular income tax previously
imposed on gifts in cash and in kind transferred by Vietnamese
living overseas to their family members and friends was now
abolished.
</P>
<P>
The official said the new income tax law aims at encouraging
more money to be sent home through the banks, the only official
transaction channel.
</P>
<P>
Those items still subject to irregular income tax include
lottery prizes, the transfer of technology, the rights to use
business patents and trademarks, technical know-how technical
designs for construction projects, industrial designs and other
services, except for those which are certified as gifts.
</P>
<P>
The deputy finance minister said that instead of the minimum
taxable 1.2 million Vietnam Dong (about 108 U.S. dollars) monthly
salary or earnings for Vietnamese citizens, the new rate was an
amount higher than 2 million Vietnam Dong (About 180 dollars) per
month.
</P>
<P>
For foreigners who are regarded as permanent residents in
Vietnam and Vietnamese people working overseas, the new threshold
before tax is paid is more than 5 million Vietnam Dong (about 440
dollars ) a month.
</P>
<P>
For foreigners who are considered non-residents in Vietnam,
their taxable income is "the total of what they earn while working
in Vietnam," according to the revised ordinance signed by
President Le Duc Anh on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ordinance also states that those individual income payers
who have an average monthly after-tax income of more than 8
million Vietnam Dong (about 720 dollars) are liable to pay an
additional 30 percent tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Items from Asia-Pacific Desk of Xinhua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
