<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Leaders Express Sorrow Over Deng's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's top leaders Thursday
expressed their deep sorrow over the death of Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping, and praised him for his contributions to China's reform
and opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
In a jointly-signed telegram to Chinese President Jiang Zemin,
Premier Li Peng and Chairman of the Chinese National People's
Congress Qiao Shi, Vietnamese Communist Party General Secretary Do
Muoi, President Le Duc Anh, Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet, and
National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc Manh said Deng's death was a
great loss to the Chinese Communist Party and the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
They described Deng, who died late on Wednesday at 93, as a
veteran leader who made "important contributions to China's causes
of revolution and liberation, national construction, and reform
and opening in particular."
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese leaders said they believe that under the
leadership of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee led by
Jiang Zemin, Chinese communists and people will continue to
implement the policy of reform and opening and build a prosperous,
modern China along the path of socialism, thus making due
contributions to peace, stability and development in the region
and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
This morning General Secretary Do Muoi, Prime Minister Vo Van
Kiet, Vice State President Nguyen Thi Binh who is on behalf of
State President Le Duc Anh, National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc
Manh and some other senior officials came to the Chinese embassy
to pay their respects to Deng Xiaoping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Further Develop Ties with China: Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Vice President Try
Sutrisno has expressed the hope that the Indonesia-China friendly
relations will further develop on a healthy way.
</P>
<P>
Try made the remarks here today when meeting with visiting
Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian and his party at the Vice
Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The vice president expressed his deepest condolences over Deng
Xiaoping's death and hoped China's current leaders would continue
the prudent domestic and international policies laid down by the
late Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
As two big countries, he noted, Indonesia and China should make
their common efforts to help establish a peaceful and fair order
for world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral ties, Try said, the exchange of visits between
high-ranking officials, military officers and peoples of the two
countries have promote mutual understandings.
</P>
<P>
The agreements, especially on economic and trade, signed by the
two sides should be realized in earnest and supported by various
quarters, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, bilateral trade between China
and Indonesia reached 3.78 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Try also briefed Chi on Indonesia's economy and its efforts to
control population and to eliminate poverty.
</P>
<P>
Chi Haotian, who arrived here Thursday on a four-day visit at
the invitation of Indonesian Defense and Security Minister Edi
Sudradjat, spoke highly of the smooth development of the
Sino-Indonesian relations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"We should make common efforts to bring the peaceful, stable
and developing world to the 21st century," chi noted.
</P>
<P>
He believed that a lasting cooperation between the governments
and armies of China and Indonesia will be conducive to peace and
stability in the region and the world.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Chi Haotian, who is also state councilor, met with
Indonesian Defense and Security Minister Edi Sudradjat during
which they exchanged views on bilateral, regional and
international issues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
