<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Accept Any Israeli-Palestinian Accord, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States no
longer advocates a full Israeli withdrawal to the 1967 borders
and will agree to whatever agreement to be reached by Israel and
Palestine, a key Israeli government adviser said today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's senior policy adviser Dore
Gold, who just returned from talks with U.S. officials, was quoted
by the English daily The Jerusalem Post as saying that the
U.S. conception of the final status of the territories had
undergone changes since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. President Ronald Reagan issued a plan that called
for full Israeli withdrawal from the territories captured in the
1967 war with Arabs, a position identical to the one expressed by
the then U.S. Secretary of State William Rogers in 1969, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a belief in the Israeli public that in (the late
U.S. President Richard) Nixon's safe there is the Rogers' plan
and that every president signs on to it," Gold was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Gold, who acknowledged the huge gap between Israeli and
Palestinian positions on the final status, said the U.S. was no
longer insistent on a withdrawal to the 1967 borders. He added
that this reflected such changes as low oil prices and the
collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
"There have been many developments in the U.S. conception on
final status," Gold said. "The U.S. prefers not to express a
position. It will agree to whatever agreement is reached by the
two parties."
</P>
<P>
Gold also said the U.S. accepted the Netanyahu government's
insistence that the Palestinians and other Arabs show reciprocity
in their relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He added that the U.S. was committed to expanding Israel's
limited relations with the Gulf states and North Africa, as well
as forging new ties with other Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian final status talks, first convened
last May but suspended so far, will settle the thorny issues of
deciding the final borders, status of Jerusalem and fate of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Until now, no date has yet been set for restarting the
final-status talks though the Netanyahu government has promised
to begin the negotiations soon following last month's signing of
Hebron agreement under the intensive U.S. mediation.
</P>
<P>
Israel's troop withdrawal from most of Hebron has also eased
tension with its Arab neighbors, which have virtually frozen the
process of normalization with the Jewish states since
Netanyahu's access to power last June.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the two sides are holding negotiations on issues
related to the interim agreement, such as the opening of safe
passages between the West Bank and Gaza Strip, the construction
of the Gaza airport and Gaza sea port, and development of
economic and security cooperations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> a d p 3182 BC-Deng-South Asia-Condolences hke -- South Asian Leaders Condole Deng's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Pakistan and
Bangladesh and an Indian minister has sent condolences messages to
the Chinese leadership, mourning the death of Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping, who passed away in Beijing on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani President Farooq Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Thursday said that they had been "deeply grieved at the
passing away of Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
In his message to Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Leghari
described Deng as "a great and revered statesman."
</P>
<P>
"He was the guiding light who steered his nation to the path of
reform, social justice and prosperity, " the Pakistani president
said, adding that Deng will be remembered as a trusted friend of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In a message to Chinese Premier Li Peng, the newly-elected
Pakistani prime minister Nawaz Sharif said, "We shall remember
Deng Xiaoping as a wise and able statesman whose enlightened
polices not only achieved laurels for the Chinese people but were
recognized the world over."
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that Deng's " contribution to regional and world
peace and stability has placed him amongst the great leaders of
modern history."
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan government has decided to hoist all flags in front
of the government buildings at half mast on February 20-25,
mourning Deng's death.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi President Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina expressed their deep condolences at the death of
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Shahabuddin Ahmed, in his message to Chinese President Jiang
Zemin, expressed his deep shock and great sorrow at the death of
Deng.
</P>
<P>
He said that China would enter the next millennium as a leading
world economic and political power by the guidance and vision of
late Deng's leadership.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina said in her message, "In his death the world has
lost an outstanding leader and a great visionary, who by his own
merit and quality of leadership, had earned for himself a
permanent place among the great leaders of modern history."
</P>
<P>
She said, Deng "was the successful architect of modern China.
He opened up China and completed its process of transition to a
leading world economic and political power that his great country
is today."
</P>
<P>
Indian External Affairs Minister I.K. Gujral, in his condolence
message, described Deng as a "colossus" who changed history and
contributed directly to building good relations between India and
China.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese leader's death would not halt the two countries'
move towards closer ties. Our relations have been moving in a
positive direction and to India's satisfaction," Gujral said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian minister said the people of India share the grief of
the people of China.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi Thursday
expressed condolences to the Chinese government and people over
Deng's death.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia acknowledged the vast contributions and
reforms made by the late Chinese leader to his nation.
</P>
<P>
Under Deng's leadership, Malaysia forged good relations with
China, which has been of mutual benefit, said the foreign
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
