<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Repeats Intention to Build Jewish Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu reiterated his decision Thursday night to
implement the controversial building plan for a large Jewish
settlement in Har Homa in East Jerusalem, reported the state-run
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told reporters in Tel Aviv that Israel will build
unconditionally and without restrictions in all parts of
Jerusalem. He added that he intends to bring his plan for
approval next week to the Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said he will also propose building houses for Arab
populations alongside the Jewish settlement in the same area. He
claimed that Israel will commit itself to allowing the Arabs to
have same status as Jewish inhabitants in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Netanyahu announced his decision to seek approval
for Har Homa project after a week of crisis in his rightwing
coalition. Some parties said they would quit if the project did
not go through and others threatened to abstain on critical vote
in Knesset (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
The internal crisis, accompanied by Palestinians' warning of
violent opposition, started over the weekend when it was reported
that the premier promised U.S. President Bill Clinton not to build
Har Homa Jewish neighborhood. But Netanyahu denied the report.
</P>
<P>
The Har Homa project was drawn up by the late prime minister
Yitzhak Rabin, but it never materialized. Shimon Peres, former
Labor prime minister and now opposition leader, said that the
project should be implemented, but the government should also
take into consideration the consequences that may arise.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat said in Ankara Thursday
that the U.S. and Russia as well as Europe should pressure Israel
not to build the Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem, which
Palestinians see as their would-be independent state.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian King Hussein Thursday also called on Israel to
consider its decision saying that the building will have negative
effect on the peace process. The king is likely to raise the issue
during Netanyahu's forthcoming visit to Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Pursues Rebel Remnants in Western Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's government troops
pursued a group of 50 rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces
(ADF) on Thursday in the western part of the country, "the New
Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The rebel remnants were forced to go out of their hideouts
after angry local people set ablaze a forest in mountains of
Mahango sub-county, western Kasese district.
</P>
<P>
Local residents complained that ADF rebel remnants hiding in
the mountain harassed them and stole their food crops and goats.
The government troops were immediately mobilized when they were
informed about the appearance of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
There were sporadic shots in the mountain on Thursday
afternoon, but local authorities can not confirm if the pursuing
detachment was engaged in a fighting with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
ADF rebels has been attempting to establish their bases in
western Kasese district since last November. But the government
troops captured the last rebel hideout in Rwenzori mountain in
Kasese district late last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
