<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Hyacinth Causes Huge Loss to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is losing one million
U.S. Dollars worth of fish every month due to speedy multiplying
of water hyacinth in the country's waters.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President and Minister of Agriculture Wandira Kazibwe
said the situation will be worsening if the weed continue
multiplying.
</P>
<P>
She said the weed has to be sprayed with weed-killer
chemicals, otherwise Ugandans would risk losing all the fish in
Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
She also discussed the matter with outgoing British High
Commissioner Edward Clay here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Water hyacinth has now strangled 90 percent of the shoreline
of rivers and lakes, a stretch of about 2,000 km. The Ugandan
government, which is choosing some places to try weed-killers, is
being criticized by some scientists.
</P>
<P>
Fishery has been playing an important role in Uganda's economy
in recent years, earning the country 20 million U.S. Dollars per
year by export. But the weed calamity is threatening its further
expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
