<HEADLINE> Mkapa Urges Opposition To Cooperate With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has called upon the opposition to cooperate with
the government in implementing his election manifesto.
</P>
<P>
Addressing rallies in Lushoto and Korogwe Districts, Eastern
Tanzania on Thursday, President Mkapa said implementation of his
manifesto was for the benefit of all people, regardless of their
political leanings.
</P>
<P>
"If we build a road, we will not put road blocks to check who
were not ruling Revolutionary Party (CCM) members," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the president praised the opposition parties for
their contribution to the prevailing peace and stability
following the 1995 general elections.
</P>
<P>
"The prevailing peace and stability has brought great honor to
our nation as some detractors thought the country would be
plunged into chaos," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said examples were abundant in Africa where some
political parties refused to accept election results and plunged
their countries into civil strife.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that unity, love and solidarity should be the
hallmark of Tanzanians, ignoring their political, religious and
racial differences.
</P>
<P>
The president added that the opposition has the right to
criticize the government's shortcomings but will not be allowed
to block its programs. 
</P>
