<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Submits Trade Complaint Against Japan to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States submitted
today a trade complaint against Japan to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) over whether Eastman Kodak has been blocked
from competing in the Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the record demonstrates that for more than 30
years, Japan has limited the sale of imported consumer
photographic film and paper in the Japanese market," said Charlene
Barshefsky, U.S. acting Trade Representative.
</P>
<P>
"To do so Japan has relied upon an extensive array of measures
designed to offset the effects of tariff, import and foreign
investment liberalization," she said.
</P>
<P>
She added it was not a commercial case between Kodak and Fuji
Photo Film Inc. of Japan, but "a trade dispute between the United
States and Japan."
</P>
<P>
Japan has until early April to reply to the U.S. statement
supported by 10 volumes of documents, before a decision is
expected to be made by WTO in October.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Fuji have both denied accusations that they have
conspired to keep Kodak out of the Japanese market. In its own
filing to the WTO, Japan said it is willing to discuss the issue
as long as the WTO also reviewed its allegations of unfair
barriers that had been erected against foreign companies in the
U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
The fight is the latest one between the U.S. and Japan after
the trade disputes over car parts, insurance and lumber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
