<HEADLINE> 50 Zimbabwean Youth Arrested in Row Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 applicants for
the national army training program turned violent in Harare on
Thursday after being told that they had failed to be recruited, a
local daily "the Herald" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The rowdy group was forced to flee when military police at the
Dzivarasekwa Army Camp, where recruitment was taking place,
threatened to open fire using live bullets.
</P>
<P>
At least four vehicles were damaged and about 50 people have
since been picked up by police.
</P>
<P>
The young people had been throwing stones at a nearby block of
flats, accusing the army of cheating and wasting their time.
</P>
<P>
Out of an initial group of more than 7,000, about 1,000
applicants were screened for further interviews, and only 100
were successfully recruited.
</P>
<P>
Investigations are still under way and the suspects are likely
to appear in court soon. 
</P>
