<HEADLINE> Chiluba Warns Against Bad Roads in Lusaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba said he was shocked at the state of disrepair of the
roads in capital Lusaka and ordered to immediately revoke the
contracts with some irresponsible companies.
</P>
<P>
During a road inspection on Thursday, the president demanded
Housing Minister Bennie Mwiinga hand in a list of all road
contractors, according to a Zambia Daily Mail report today.
</P>
<P>
After seeing Lusaka's major roads which were in what he
described as a "shameful" state, Chiluba said it was corruption
and he was suspicious about the relations between the firms and
some government officials.
</P>
<P>
"I am directing that the roads be dug out completely and work
must be certified professionally before commencement. It is not
right that roads be re-done every year," said Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the bad roads in the city contributed to
the high crime rate involving car thefts as most of the vehicles
are grabbed at a gun point after failing to drive on the good
roads. 
</P>
