<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anniversary of Shanghai Communique Marked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Acting Secretary of State
Peter Tarnoff and several former U.S. secretaries of state
gathered in New York on Thursday to mark the 25th anniversary of
the Shanghai Communique, which reopened the door to Sino-U.S.
relations and initiated the normalization process.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. secretaries of state Dr. Henry Kissinger, Cyrus
Vance, Alexander M. Haig and William P. Rogers attended the
ceremony. Chinese Ambassador to the United States Li Daoyu was
also present.
</P>
<P>
In a greeting message, which was read out at the ceremony,
U.S. President Clinton expressed his "appreciation" for the former
secretaries attending the event and "recognition" of them in
making that historical moment and of their follow-up activities
that brought the United States and China closer.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that he is exercising the exact engagment policy
towards China that has been exercised in the past quarter of
century.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger began a speech by reading a letter from Former
President Bush, who said "It is not a secret that no bilateral
relationship is more important to world peace than the U.S.-China
relationship." He commended all those who have helped facilitate
U.S. relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
In recalling the signing of the historic communique, Kissinger
noted specially that it did not only list what the two sides
agreed but also what they didn't. He hoped the U.S. government to
apply lessons of the Cold War to the current Chinese-American
relations.
</P>
<P>
Vance and Haig all highly valued the Shanghai Communique,
hoping both China and the United States to solve the present
tensions and problems through patient dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Li Daoyu said the best way to commemorate the Shanghai
Communique is for both China and the United States to emulate the
vision and courage exemplified by the leaders of the two countries
25 years ago and to reaffirm and carry forward the principles of
the three Sino-US Joint Communiques.
</P>
<P>
"History had testified," he said, "that if both sides put our
relations in a global, strategic and long-term perspective, if
both sides handle bilateral differences in accordance with the
three Joint Communiques and through consultations in the spirit of
mutual respect and equality, we can gradually narrow down our
differences and resolve them."  
</P>
</TEXT>
