<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Record Number of Nature Reserve Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- there are 14,000 workers in
China's nature reserves, more than in any other country in the
world, according to recent statistics from the Ministry of
Forestry.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that China's wildlife reserves occupy more
than 6.4 percent of the country's total land area, also the
highest figure in the world.
</P>
<P>
China began to establish wild plant and animal reserves in the
1950s, and there are now 574 nature reserves and 71 of them are at
the national level.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, there are more than 2,000 wildlife
researchers employed by various institutes at the national level,
and about 1,000 officials working in the related government
offices.
</P>
<P>
"In China, more people indirectly serve nature protection. For
example, there are 30,000 members in the China Association for
Wild Animal Protection," Wang Zhibao, Vice-Minister of Forestry,
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, awareness of the need to protect nature has
significantly increased both among officials and among ordinary
people in China.
</P>
<P>
"Soinam Daje, a Tibetan official, has devoted his life to the
protection of rare animals, and a film made of his story is being
shown across the country," the vice-minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
