<HEADLINE> Foreign-funded Firms Become Export Source In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Foreign-funded enterprises
contributed 51 percent to the total export volume of east China's
Shandong Province last year, according to recent statistics.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the provincial commission on foreign trade
and economic cooperation show that foreign-backed firms in the
province earned 5.49 billion US dollars from exports in 1996, up
35.2 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
There were 900 foreign-funded enterprises each doing over one
million dollars in export business, 80 of which exceed 10 million
dollars, according to the commission.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government took steps to promote exports among
the foreign-funded enterprises last year, said a leading official
with the commission.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that foreign-funded enterprises made 1.27
billion dollars from exports of primary products, which
contributed 23.2 percent to the total amount of export.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises earned 4.22 billion dollars from exports of
manufactured goods, with mechanical and electrical goods and
machinery being the major items.
</P>
<P>
The province exports to over 70 countries and regions, with
South Korea being the biggest market. Exports to Japan, the US,
Hong Kong, Singapore, and Taiwan all exceeded 50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
