<HEADLINE> Four-time Olympian Zheng Haixia to Play for WNBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Zheng Haixia, who led the
Chinese women's basketball team to the silver medal at the 1994
World Championship, will play for the the American league WNBA in
its inaugural season, the league said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The WNBA said joining the four-time Olympian Zheng at the WNBA
are three Americans who currently play in the Italian League --
Wanda Guyton, Kym Hampton and Bridget Pettis.
</P>
<P>
Zheng, a 2.04-meter center from China's Henan Province, was
voted the Most Valuable Player at the 1994 World Championship in
Australia, where she averaged 26 points and 13.2 rebounds per game
and shot 84 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
Zheng, who did not miss Olympic Games since 1984, paced China
to a silver at Barcelona in 1992 and averaged 18.1 points per game
at Atlanta last summer when China dropped down to ninth.
</P>
<P>
Guyton, a 1.85-meter forward, is currently playing for Italy's
Ferrara, 1.87-meter center Hampton is with Pavia while Pettis, a
1.78-meter guard, now plays for Faenza.
</P>
<P>
Zheng, Guyton, Hampton and Pettis round out the second group of
16 players who will play in its inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
The league will hold a elite draft via conference call on
February 27, when the eight WNBA teams will select next two
players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
