<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong to Continue Steady Economic Progress This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province will maintain its steady economic progress this year,
"China Daily" quoted Guangdong Governor Lu Ruihua as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the local legislature, Lu estimated that the local
gross domestic product would increase ten percent this year. Total
GDP volume was 609.7 billion yuan (73.46 billion US dollars) last
year, up 11 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
In a report on government work, Lu said the inflation rate has
been at 4.4 percent, much lower than the ten percent targeted last
year.
</P>
<P>
Macro-control strategy has operated efficiently. The total
fixed asset investment increase was held at five percent to 244.3
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production volume increased by 18 percent, with
large enterprise groups taking up 40 percent of the total gross
output and 80 percent of the profits.
</P>
<P>
Import and export volume reached 110 billion US dollars, with
59 billion US dollars for export.
</P>
<P>
A better investment environment and a more equal treatment
policy between domestic firms and overseas-funded firms have
helped boost the use of overseas funds. Actual use of overseas
investment reached 13.9 billion US dollars, a 15 percent increase
from 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, Lu pointed out some problems such as the decreasing
enterprise profit level, stockpiles, deficits, bad loans and
unreasonable economic fix.
</P>
<P>
Upon Hong Kong's return to the motherland in July, the governor
called for the province to seize the chance to advance jointly
with Hong Kong in trading, finance, technology and education areas.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong should take the opportunity to attract more capital
from Hong Kong and Macao and upgrade export products and further
develop a sound export processing system.
</P>
<P>
Export companies are encouraged to unite to set up
conglomerates to be more competitive.
</P>
<P>
Electronics, information technology, light industry and
textile, petro-chemicals and machinery are key areas to be
supported by the government.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural development and economic structure reform will be
placed at the top of the government's working agenda this year.
</P>
<P>
Lu emphasized the protection of arable land and affirmed that
grain growing areas should be no less than 33.3 million ha and
annual output at about 19 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors to Review Reform's Progress in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of 30 donor
organizations, such as the World Bank and Asian Development Bank,
will hold a mid-term review of aid utilization by the Bangladeshi
government on February 25, according to Finance Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
The review meeting, to be held in Dhaka, will mainly focus on
four important areas including the banking and financial sector,
privatization, poverty alleviation and water resource management,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the whole gamut of the reform agenda, which the
government is expected to implement in the light of the
understanding reached at the Paris consortium meeting last
September, would come up for review.
</P>
<P>
Following the Ganges water-sharing agreement with India, the
water resource development will be given priority because of its
crucial role in changing human life style, said the sources,
adding that the upcoming two-day meeting would devote a whole
working session to the issue.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that such a donor's meeting is taking
place in the capital city of Bangladesh, who receives about 2
billion US dollars of foreign aid every year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Optimistic About China's Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is optimistic
about China's agriculture, according to Pieter Bottelier, chief of
the bank's China resident mission, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The country has great potential in grain production, which can
be developed through increasing crop land yield, applying advanced
technology and reducing grain losses, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicate that more than 60 percent of
China's 100 million ha of crop land produce low yields. The
average production is equal to 60 percent of that in countries
with advanced agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that spending an average 2,600 yuan (316 US
dollars) per ha of low-yield land would help raise grain output by
45 million tons, which is about four times the country's grain
imports last year.
</P>
<P>
Only 35 percent of the grain production growth is due to the
introduction of new technology. This leaves big room for growth
because the figure in countries with advanced agriculture is 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture wants to improve technology's
contribution rate to 50 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government also has taken measures to expand its farmland
acreage by cultivating barren land and reclaiming wasteland.
</P>
<P>
After declining 267,000 ha from 1986 to the early 1990s, crop
land is recovering by increasing more than 130,000 ha annually.
</P>
<P>
Opportunities also lie in cutting back on grain losses from
poor storage and transportation conditions which have resulted in
losing more than ten percent of the total grain output, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 million tons will be saved if the country reduces
the loss rate to the international average level of five percent,
they said. China produced 48 million tons of grain in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although the country imports more than ten million tons of
grain annually, it also exports some grain and a large quantity of
other agricultural products, noted Bottelier.
</P>
<P>
In fact, China last year achieved a surplus in its foreign
trade of agricultural products, according to official
statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
