<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-owned Farms Go under Contract System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- State-owned farms previously
called People's Liberation Army reclamation farms across the
country's remote areas will allow individual households to
contract their farmland for agricultural production this year.
</P>
<P>
Today's "China Daily" quoted officials with the Ministry of
Agriculture as saying that introducing a household contract
responsibility system to the state farms is part of a reform to
tap the potential of their employee's enthusiasm for production.
</P>
<P>
These state farms have an agricultural administrative system
similar to the former People's Communes.
</P>
<P>
They lease land to private businesses and contract farmland to
their employees to make everyone involved responsible for their
own profits and losses.
</P>
<P>
With 4.53 million ha of arable land, state farms have become
the country's leading producer of cotton, natural rubber, milk and
soy beans.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the farms produced more than 15 million tons of
grain and soy beans, up 21 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, they also yielded 538,200 tons of cotton, 7.8 million
tons of sugar crops, 700,000 tons of meat, 380,000 tons of aquatic
products and 1.06 million tons of cow milk.
</P>
<P>
Tapping the potential of agricultural production of state farms
not only requires the enthusiasm of individuals but also needs
advanced agro-technology and farm machinery.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year state farms had 10.22 million kw in
combined power of farm machinery to modernize their agricultural
production. This enabled them to use farm equipment on 79 percent
of their crop-sowing areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
