<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number Of Chain Stores Growing In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The chain store business is
expanding steadily in this east China metropolis, with more than
2,000 in operation now and plans for 1000 chain supermarkets by
the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Sales of the chain-store business, which is a focal point in
Shanghai's retail sales development plan, are expected to reach 16
billion yuan by then, accounting for ten percent of total sales.
</P>
<P>
Supermarket growth is the most notable of all stores, said Hong
Guankang, vice director and general secretary of the Shanghai
Chain-Business Association.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 800 supermarkets have opened since 1991. In 1996,
supermarket sales were more than four billion yuan, accounting for
about three percent of the city's retail sales, compared with 2.3
billion yuan and 2.4 percent in 1995, said Hong.
</P>
<P>
He said the city has about 700 convenience stores, 70
restaurant franchises, 100 clothing-chain stores, and laundry,
household appliance repair, and photo service chains.
</P>
<P>
Hong predicts that business will expand to include medicines,
capital goods, hotels, and travel services. With their
increasingly popularity because of availability and low prices,
more local enterprises intend to join in.
</P>
<P>
Some businesses are going nationwide. The Shanghai No. 1
Department Store Co. Ltd. has opened outlets in the cities of
Changchun, Chongqing, Hefei, Xi'an, and Taiyuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
