<HEADLINE> IOC Reports on 2004 Bidding Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 20 hke -- A report of the International
Olympic Committee (IOC) revealed Thursday that Rome, Buenos Aires,
Athens and Cape Town are the best-placed bids for hosting the 2004
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The IOC released the report from Lausanne, Switzerland and will
announce a shortlist of four or five cities from the original 11
candidates on March 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
Lille, St Petersburg, Stockholm, Sevilla, San Juan, Istanbul
and Rio de Janeiro are the other candidates.
</P>
<P>
The IOC evaluation committee emphasized Rome's professionalism
of the bid and the immense experience of the Italians in
organizing large sporting events.
</P>
<P>
The commission reported Buenos Aires offered the good
facilities for football, the excellent tennis courts, and the
sites planned for judo and gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
It was issued about the calm environment of the Olympic village
which was near the town center and the good transport and
telecommunications infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Athens had an excellent stadium 15 minutes from the Olympic
village, but the commission admitted major problems regarding
transport from the airport and transport into the town.
</P>
<P>
As regards Cape Town, the commission said the quality of
accommodation planned in the city was very good.  
</P>
</TEXT>
