<HEADLINE> Russian Leaders Meet U.S. Secretary of State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov held talks
today with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
bilateral ties and NATO's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin told Albright that economic cooperation between
the two countries is much more active than political links,
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency gave no further details, but Albright reportedly
outlined proposals for a charter to link Russia to NATO and for
further cutting the arms ceilings imposed under the 1990
Conventional Forces in Europe treaty on tanks and other weaponry
deployed in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also exchanged views on preparations for a
Russian-U.S. summit in Helsinki next month, she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright's spokesman, Nicholas Burns, described the
meetings as "very constructive and very detailed", saying the
meetings took place in a "warm atmosphere".
</P>
<P>
However, Russian officials repeatedly said before Albright
arrived that they remained implacably opposed to NATO's
enlargement, which they regard as a threat to Russian security.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin is scheduled meet Albright on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here this afternoon for a two-day visit,
aimed at softening Russia's opposition to NATO's expansion.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is the sixth stop in Albright's nine-country tour to
Europe and Asia, which has so far taken her to Italy, Germany,
France, Britain and the NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
