<HEADLINE> Central China Factories With Pollution Problems Moved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen factories in Yichang,
which is along the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, have been
moved out of the city proper or have stopped production in a move
to remove the clouds of smoke that darken the city's sky.
</P>
<P>
Another 48 factories with big pollution problems will also be
moved to Yichang's outskirts soon and technological improvements
will be made before they can move to Yichang's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Xiling Gorge in Yichang, in central China's Hubei Province, is
one of the Three Gorges, and a well known tourist spot, with
several million tourist arrivals every year.
</P>
<P>
However, the soot discharged by some factories has seriously
damaged the city's image. So, the city government decided to move
66 factories, valued at 740 million yuan (92 million
U.S. dollars), to the outskirts.
</P>
<P>
The move will cost 2.19 billion yuan (267 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
A pottery factory moved from the downtown area to a suburban
area and replaced the heavy oil it uses with light diesel oil,
putting an end to the black smoke in its rebuilt factory.
</P>
<P>
The city government has drafted preferential policies to
encourage factories with pollution problems to move out of the
urban area and has established an industrial park in a suburban
area for the purpose.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
