<HEADLINE> UN Chief Calls for Cooperation on Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 20 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Thursday called for intensified
international cooperation as the world embarked on a new and final
phase of the peace process in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Second Ministerial Meeting of the Special
Conference to Support the Peace Process in Liberia, Annan said it
was no secret what needed to be done by the international
community if the peace processes in Liberia were to have the best
chance of succeeding.
</P>
<P>
Among the tasks he listed were the provision of more troops
and resources to the peace-keeping force of the Economic Community
of Western Africa, encouraging demobilized fighters to return to
civil society and reactivating basic institutions of government
and society.
</P>
<P>
He said all the tasks could be completed. He urged participants
of the meeting to pay more attention to the unification of the
international community in promoting peace process in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, the failure of the principal external actors to
maintain a common political approach to the Liberian crisis
undoubtedly impeded political progress towards a solution," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Today, by contrast, a positive trend in the peace process owed
much to efforts to bring greater political cohesion to the main
groups involved.
</P>
<P>
"This cooperation must now be intensified as we embark on a new
final phase of the peace process in Liberia," he said. "We must
all be committed to a common approach, as well as to a common
strategy for implementation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
