<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western European, North American Leaders Mourn Deng's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from Western European
and North American countries paid tribute to Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping who died on Wednesday at the age of 93, praising him for
his outstanding contributions to China and the world.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday expressed sorrow over
Deng's death, describing him as an "extraordinary figure" on the
world stage.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past two decades, Mr. Deng was an extraordinary
figure on the world stage and the driving force behind China's
decision to normalize relations with the United States," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
"China today plays an important role in world affairs in no
small part because of Mr. Deng's decision to open his country to
the outside world."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright who was in London as
part of her world tour said Wednesday that the United States
obviously views Deng Xiaoping as a historical figure in China.
</P>
<P>
"Deng played a role in normalizing relations between the
U.S. and China and he is to be remembered for that," she said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien issued a statement on
Wednesday night, expressing his condolences at the death of the
Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the government of Canada and all Canadians, I
extend my condolences to the family of Deng Xiaoping, the
Government of China and the Chinese people," Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister John Major's office said Thursday that
"Deng's initiative played a crucial part in creating today's
economically dynamic and successful China."
</P>
<P>
Former British Prime Minister Baroness Thatcher praised Deng as
"a man of vision and leadership who profoundly changed the life of
the Chinese people for the better."
</P>
<P>
Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio, who was in Macao on a
six-day visit, praised Deng as a man as great as "Dr. Sun Yat-Sen
and Mao Zedong, whose life and political course were unseparable
from the history of China."
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl also paid tribute to Deng, saying
his initiatives to open China to the world laid the foundation for
long-term "close and trusting" relations between Germany and China.
</P>
<P>
"The impressive economic progress of China, which is evident to
the entire world, stems above all from Deng's influence," Kohl
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac sent a message of condolence to
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, expressing his deep sorrow over
Deng's death.
</P>
<P>
He said that Deng will be remembered as the architect of
China's reform over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said the death of Deng
Xiaoping had deprived China of "the father of its great economic
reforms" and the world of "one of the most prominent personalities
of the century."
</P>
<P>
The Dutch government said on Wednesday that Deng's death was a
great loss for: his initiatives to open China to the world laid
the foundation for
</P>
<P>
Thomas Klestil, the Austrian president, said Thursday that
Deng's death has deprived China of a "great reformer, who has made
decisive contribution to the development of China's economy and
its open-door policy."
</P>
<P>
Jacques Santer, president of the European Commission, the
executive arm of the 15-member European Union, said Thursday that
"the mark Deng Xiaoping has made on the 20th century shall be
remembered by the whole world well into the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Deng's leadership had made an immense contribution to
modernization and economic reform in China, and to the opening up
the country to the rest of the world, Santer said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his confidence that Deng's legacy will
"benefit not only all the people of China but their partners in
the region and in the wider world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
