<HEADLINE> Beijing to Expand Infrastructure Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will spend more on
building up its infrastructure in a move to achieve its goal of
becoming a modernized international city, the city's acting mayor
Jia Qinglin said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ongoing fifth session of the city's Tenth
People's Congress, Jia said that about 100 billion yuan (about 12
billion US dollars) of funds will be needed to support the
infrastructure programs for the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
These include a group of key projects involving construction of
systems for water, electricity, heat and roads,
telecommunications, ports and environmental protection. They are
expected to help increase the city's daily water supply to 600,000
cubic meters, and the electricity generating capacity to seven
million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, the city will begin transporting
natural gas from Shaanxi and Gansu provinces and Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region, build 11 kilometers of new subway lines, and
increase the number of telephone lines to five million, which
means that 55 percent of urban families will have telephones.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will continue to introduce foreign funds into the
infrastructure improvement plan and the renovation of rundown
houses, Jia noted, adding that it will also update the system used
for buying houses and increase the mortgage loans for individual
housing purchases, Jia noted.
</P>
<P>
The city will build eight million square meters of new housing,
renovate 1.1 million square meters of dilapidated houses and
complete 600,000 square meters of "comfortable housing" for
households with low incomes, he said.
</P>
<P>
He recalled the progress made in the infrastructure upgrading
in 1996, stressing that the future construction should be
well-guided by comprehensive city planning.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the 30-kilometer expressway connecting
Beijing and Changping went into operation, the renovation work of
some major streets was completed, and the two major electricity
generators in the Shisanling Power Station were built, Jia said.
</P>
<P>
The city's electricity generating capacity increased by more
than 400,000 kilowatts, and the number of gas users went up by
8,700 last year, Jia said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
