<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Steps up Fight Against Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Colombia and the
United States signed an agreement today which opens the way for
them to intercept suspected drug-running boats beyond the 12-mile
coastal limit.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Colombian Foreign Minister Maria
Emma Mejia Velez and U.S. Ambassador to Colombia Myles Frechette.
</P>
<P>
The agreement comes in the wake of new laws allowing the
expropriation of money made from drug trafficking and the more
than doubling of maximum jail terms for traffickers from 24 to
60 years.
</P>
<P>
Officials hope these two measures will help Colombia win back
"certification" from the U.S., naming it an ally in the
international war against drugs and thus eliminating the threat of
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton is due to decide on February 27
whether or not to certify Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Last year Colombia lost its certification as the U.S. didn't
believe it was doing enough to fight the drug war, and suffered
sanctions such as a cut in military assistance and vetos on loans
from international banks where the United States has influence.
</P>
<P>
Frechette said the signing of the treaty and the new
legislation will be put on the scales when the certification
decision is made.
</P>
<P>
The United States has long complained about the prison terms
for convicted drug traffickers in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
It protested vigorosly that the sentences meted out to the
leaders of the Cali drug cartel in January were too lenient.
Gilberto and Miguel Rodriguez Orejuela were jailed for nine and
10.5 years respectively.
</P>
<P>
If they had been sentenced under the new legislation,
they would be facing between 45 and 60 years in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0259 </DOCNO>
