<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia, U.S. to Combat Maritime Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Colombia and the
United States signed an agreement today which opens the way for
them to intercept suspected drug-running boats beyond the 12-mile
coastal limit.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Colombian Foreign Minister Maria
Emma Mejia Velez and U.S. Ambassador to Colombia Myles Frechette.
</P>
<P>
The agreement and the laws that permit to expropriate the
fortunes of the drug traffickers and condemn them to 60 years in
prison are compatible with the Vienna Convention commitments
against international drug trafficking, Mejia said.
</P>
<P>
Political and congressional leaders said the legislative
measures and the naval agreement are a Colombian effort to obtain
from the United States the annual certification of support to the
international war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Last year Colombia was not certified and suffered some
sanctions such as a cut in military assistance and vetos to loans
from international banks, in which the United States has a
major participation.
</P>
<P>
Frechette said the signing of the treaty and the law that
increases the penalties will be put on the scales at the moment of
taking the decision and granting or denying the certification.
</P>
<P>
The international community received with respect and elation
the Colombian decision to increase penalties for drug trafficking
kingpins.
</P>
<P>
The United States had protested the leniency shown in the
nine-year and 10.5-year jail terms dictated recently to the
Gilberto and Miguel Rodriguez Orejuela brothers, confessed leaders
of the Cali cartel.
</P>
<P>
If they had been sentenced according to the new legislation,
they would have been sentenced to a 60-year maximum or a minimum
of 45 years in jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
