<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico To Repay IMF $600 Million in Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government
will make a 600 million U.S, dollar advance repayment on former
loans to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) before the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
The repayment was announced today by the Finance and Public
Credit Ministry (SHCP).
</P>
<P>
Finance authorities said the prepayment was made possible by
the reception of 1.18 billion dollars resulting from Federal
Government bonds sales in German marks and Italian lire during
February 20 and 24.
</P>
<P>
The bonds issued on the German market add up to 1.5 million
marks (about 880 million dollars), and 5 billion lire in Italy
(300 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Mexican bond issues in these markets have 12-year and
10-year maturities, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The SHCP said 50 percent of the resources obtained would be
used for the prepayment to the IMF, and the other half would be
channeled to international reserves, which reached 18.5 billion
dollars in recent days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
