<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Discuss Security Issues With Saudis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
discuss security issues with Saudi Arabia's Prince Sultan when he
visits Washington next week, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan is coming "as an emissary of King Fahd in his
capacity as deputy prime minister, and he will meet with a range
of people while he's here," Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon told
reporters at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
U.S. troops stationed in Saudi Arabia have been threatened with
various kinds of attacks since their presence there after the Gulf
War in 1991. On June 25 last year, 19 American servicemen were
killed when a truck bomb exploded at their Khobar Tower housing
facilities at a military air base in Dhahran.
</P>
<P>
The United States has henceforth moved its troops there to a
far remote air base less vulnerable to attacks, and taken even
more tightened security measures to protect its servicemen's life.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan will discuss with Defense Secretary William Cohen
"our program to improve the security of the U.S. military people
serving in Saudi Arabia to protect our interests in the Middle
East," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
He said investigations into the June 25 bomb attack would be on
the agenda when they hold talks.
</P>
<P>
The United States has repeatedly expressed its frustration over
the slow pace of Saudis' probe into the bomb attack with the FBI
chief and the justice secretary coming out to make public
criticism, complaining Saudis' lack of cooperation in the
investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
