<HEADLINE> Canadian Plane Maker Lands More Jet Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Bombardier Inc. has
lined up 1.5 billion U.S. dollars in likely orders for its stretch
version of Canadair Regional Jet, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
France's Brit Air will become the first to fly the new Canadair
jet, which is to be formally known as the CRJ-700.
</P>
<P>
The French regional carrier has placed firm orders for four
70-seat CRJ-700 and taken out an option on two more. It is
scheduled to take delivery of the first plane in the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Seven other buyers on four continents have put down payments on
a further 61 planes, leaving the company with a total of 67 firm
orders, options and memorandums of understanding, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The CRJ-700 jet is priced at 23 million dollars and has entered
the final stages of design, according to Bombardier Inc., Canada's
largest transportation conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
The new plane is intended to appeal to airlines that are trying
to reduce fleet costs by matching the size of their aircraft to
consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
"We forecast a requirement for about 2,000 regional jet
aircraft in the 20- to 90-seat market by the year 2015," said
Pierre Lortie, president of the Bombardier Regional Aircraft
Division.
</P>
<P>
"Bombardier's share of the jet portion of this market -- 53
percent in calendar 1996 year alone -- will be further reinforced
by the Canadair Regional Jet Series 700," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
