<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-20 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nile Basin Countries Discuss Water Issues in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Nile Basin countries opened a
meeting here today to discuss projects to develop the rich
resources of the world's second longest river.
</P>
<P>
When inaugurating the fifth meeting of the Nile Basin
countries, Egyptian Deputy Premier and Minister of Agriculture
Youssef Wali, said that water resources of the Nile River are not
fully exploited.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has proposed the "Techno-Nile" gathering as a technical
arrangement for laying down an integrated framework of action in
the interests of the Nile Basin countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting of nine water resources ministers will
discuss the plan of action agreed in previous meeting in Tanzania
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian MENA news agency quoted Egyptian Nile Water
Authority Chairman Mohamed Nasser as saying that the plan included
22 long-range development projects for the Nile water resources
and environment protection with investment totaling 100 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nasser said the meeting will be followed by a conference in
Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, on February 23-28 to discuss the research
work in the best way to develop the Nile resources.
</P>
<P>
Flowing into Egypt, the 6,700-kilometer-long Nile fans out a
fertile valley of 24,000 square kilometers which accounts for
two-thirds of the Egyptian arable land and attracts 96 percent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1959 agreement on the quota share between Egypt and
Sudan, Egypt has access to 55.5 billion cubic meters of the Nile
water, which forms 99 percent of the country's sweet water
resources.
</P>
<P>
The Nile Basin groups Egypt, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda,
Burundi, Kenya, Zaire and Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970221.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Urges Lockerbie Trial in Scotland Or US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 20 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John
Major said here today that two Libyans suspected of planting a
bomb in an American airline should be tried in Scotland or the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the British parliament earlier today, Major said,
"I believe the trial should either be in Scotland, which is the
preference, or the United States."
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans have been indicted of blowing up Pan American
flight 103 over Lockerbie in Scotland, killing 259 people on board
and 11 others on the ground.
</P>
<P>
"We would like a solution as much as the relatives but we need
a proper criminal trial and there are genuine and practical
difficulties in trying to establish such a trial in a third
country," Major said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Libyan government has suggested that
it would hand over the two men for trial in the Hague or any third
country, but London and Washington have rejected the offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
