<HEADLINE> Ghana's Economy Up 5.2 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Ghana recorded a 5.2 percent
economic growth in 1996, slightly higher than the projected five
percent increase for the year.
</P>
<P>
The country saw a four percent rise in agriculture, 4.2
percent hike in the industrial sector and 6.3 percent growth in
the service sector, Finance Minister Kwame Peprah quoted by a
report reaching here today as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation in the western African country dropped
from 70.8 percent at the end of 1995 to 32.6 percent in December
1996, Peprah told the newly-elected parliament on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The crops and livestock sub-sector grew by six percent and the
manufacturing sector rose by 3.3 percent last year, said Peprah,
adding mining and quarrying went up by 4.2 percent and
the construction sub-sector up by 6.1 percent in the period.
</P>
<P>
Higher growth rates were also observed in the forestry,
logging and fishing sub-sectors in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Ghana's receipts last year stood at 2,268.5 Cedis
(1.29 billion Dollars) while expenditures came to 2,410.5 billion
Cedis (1.37 billion Dollars), according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The deficit, the minister said, is caused by "many
challenges" in managing the 1996 fiscal program. enditem


=02202128

=02202134
NNNN
05:34 05:34 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
