<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-20 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President: Cyprus Tries to Solve its Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 20 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said today that the Greek Cypriot side is not seeking a
solution to the Cyprus problem through military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The president was speaking at a gathering on "1997, a year
for Cyprus", which was held in Athens this evening, according to
the Cyprus News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The first message I wish to send out in all directions,
including Turkey, is that we are not seeking a solution of the
Cyprus problem by military confrontation, but by effective
peaceful procedures," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
He left here today for Athens to take part in the gathering.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his second message is that despite the
"irrevocable decision" to solve the problem through peaceful
means, "we shall continue with our defense program and acquire
the high technology weapons we consider necessary and which, as
an independent and sovereign country, we are entitled to acquire
for a more effective defense."
</P>
<P>
He said this policy will continue as long as there are Turkish
troops in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a joint defense pact between Cyprus and Greece,
President Clerides said "the moment Turkey withdraws its
occupation troops from Cyprus and the island is demilitarized,
there will be no need for the joint defense pact."
</P>
<P>
The government has an obligation to ensure the security of
its people and seek maximum protection of the sovereignty,
independence and territorial integrity of the Republic, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come to make a more persistent and decisive
effort to achieve a solution of the Cyprus problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his government's determination to work in this
direction with sincerity and an open mind with the U.N. and all
those who support their efforts.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides also expressed readiness for face-to-face
talks with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in 1997, "as
soon as the ground is properly prepared to ensure their
success."
</P>
<P>
However, he noted he is not prepared to begin another round
of fruitless talks as in the past.
</P>
<P>
Concluding his speech, the president said his government is
ready for a "sensible compromise" to reach a solution in Cyprus,
but warned that "if the Turkish forces try to impose a solution,
Cyprus will be more than ready to respond."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
