<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Rules out Quick Resumption of Syrian-Israli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. State Department
Spokesman Nicholas Burns ruled out today the quick resumption of
Israel's peace negotiations with Syria and Lebanon, which was
suspended one year ago.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Paris-based Orient Radio, which was
monitored in Beirut, Burns said Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu briefed the U.S. leaders about Israeli positions on
its peace talks with Syria during his visit to Washington last
week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. department spokesman told the Arabic-language radio
that Washington will make contacts with Damascus, but admitted
that it is difficult to bring the Syrian and Israeli negotiators
together at present.
</P>
<P>
"I don't expect movements soon," Burns said, "Prime Minister
Netanyahu gave us some ideas. We are going to be in communication
with the Syrian government."
</P>
<P>
"We want to see Syria and Israel to resume their
negotiations, I think it's hard to get them to do that," said
the U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the resumption of the peace talks is in
the interest of Syria and Israel, adding that U.S. President
Bill Clinton has "very clear" views on this issue.
</P>
<P>
On the role played by France in the Middle East, Burns
underlined, "The United States has always welcomed a French
cooperation in the Middle East, and we continue to do so. France
has a long role, a historical role and a present role, and
France has good relations with many countries in the Middle
East."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration will concentrate its diplomacy
on the Middle East in the next month, the U.S. official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
